# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cornell-university
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Port of New York Authority began acquiring the land on the building's site in 1930, against the protests of local residents.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] It was completed in 1932 and served as an inland terminal for the Hudson River piers and as a warehousing and industrial facility.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Occupancy fell to 50 percent in the 1970s due to the decline of industrial activity in Manhattan, and the Port Authority itself moved to the World Trade Center in 1973.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] In the 1990s the building began to attract tenants in the technology and telecommunications sectors.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] In 2010, the building was purchased for $1.8 billion by Google, who became its largest tenant; Google's presence helped attract other technology companies to Chelsea and contributed to the neighborhood's ongoing gentrification.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Aside from Google, the building is also home to a cancer treatment center and a black box theater.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] 111 Eighth Avenue occupies the full city block between Eighth and Ninth Avenues and 15th and 16th Streets in the Chelsea neighborhood of Manhattan, New York City.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building, completed in 1932, was designed by Lusby Simpson of Abbott, Merkt & Co.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building is 15 stories tall and has 2.9 million square feet (270,000 m2) of floor space, more than the Empire State Building; the individual floors are nearly 4 acres (1.6 ha) in area and have 14.5-foot (4.4 m) ceilings.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] It has a rooftop helipad and penthouse floors on either end of the building.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Its exterior is in the Art Deco style and features recurring seagull motifs.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The walls are largely made of brick, with granite bases; the first two stories are limestone, and copings and finials are of terracotta.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Because of the warehouse mission of the building, it was able to avoid some of the setback rules that greatly reduced the buildable space available for the skyscrapers that mark the Manhattan skyline.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building had a multipurpose design when it opened in 1932, with the first floor and basement designated as "Union Inland Terminal #1", which was to be used to transport goods by truck to and from railroad lines and shipping piers on the Hudson River.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Cargo was dropped off along 15th Street, sorted inside the building, and picked up from the 16th Street side.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building included four truck elevators, each of which had a 40,000-pound (18,000 kg; 20-short-ton) capacity and could travel at up to 200 ft/min (61 m/min).
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] These elevators measured 17 by 34 feet (5.2 by 10.4 m) across, and they lifted trucks into pits measuring 3.5 feet (1.1 m) deep and 38 by 90 feet (12 by 27 m) across.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] There were also 12 package elevators and 18 passenger elevators.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Freight companies used the elevators to deliver cargo directly to tenants, in contrast to other industrial buildings in New York City, where cargo was dropped off at ground level.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The second floor contained Commerce Hall, designed for exhibitions.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The upper floors were intended for manufacturing.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] There were 16 loading docks on each floor.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] On the 15th floor, which contained the Port Authority's offices, engineer Aymar Embury II designed a 325-seat auditorium decorated in green and blue.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The *New York Herald Tribune* said was the "first auditorium designed for commercial purposes in a strictly commercial structure".
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building's design retains vestiges of its original industrial purpose, including truck-sized freight elevators and floors built to support heavy loads.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] As of 2008, two of its original truck elevators were still in use, in addition to nine other large freight elevators and fourteen passenger elevators.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The floors of the two lobbies originally each had a large bronze seal of the Port Authority embedded in them; one of these was removed and converted into a coffee table as a retirement gift for Port Authority director Austin J.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] It is also noted for its unobstructed views of the Manhattan skyline.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building has direct access to the 14th Street/Eighth Avenue station of the New York City Subway; when the building opened, a staircase at 15th Street and Eighth Avenue led directly to the subway station in the basement.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] By the early twentieth century, the West Side of Manhattan was plagued with heavy traffic because of the tangle of street-level passenger and freight trains on the West Side Line, cargo unloading from the busy Hudson River piers, and the lack of suitable warehouse facilities.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The situation led the Port of New York Authority to commission the construction of a large inland terminal at 111 Eighth Avenue.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] It was designed to alleviate the traffic problem by streamlining the distribution of goods within a single location.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Instead of cargo being picked up directly at the piers, it would be brought to the building to be consolidated, where trucks could pick up all their cargo in a single stop.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] A concurrent project, the West Side Improvement Project, replaced the West Side Line with the original High Line elevated railway, which ran a few blocks away from 111 Eighth Avenue; it began full operation in 1934.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] In May 1930, the Port Authority and all of the railroads in the Port of New York agreed to build a "union inland freight terminal" between Eighth Avenue, 15th Street, Ninth Avenue, and 16th Street.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal was planned to cost $15 million and would include office space, as well as large driveways and about 7 acres (28,000 m2; 300,000 ft2) for sorting freight.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The structure was to be known as Inland Terminal No.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] 1 because the Port Authority hoped that similar freight terminals would be constructed across the city.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] At the time of the announcement, the Port Authority already owned half of the block, which it had acquired for $1.5 million.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Most of the block had been occupied by houses, except for a factory in the middle of the block on 15th Street.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The New York City Board of Estimate approved the proposed terminal's site in June 1930.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority acquired additional land on the building's site throughout the rest of the year, despite the protests of local residents.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] By October 1930, the Port Authority had bought 85 percent of the site and was preparing to acquire the remaining buildings through condemnation.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] A contract for the demolition of existing structures was awarded in December 1930.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Twelve railroads signed an agreement with the Port Authority to use the new terminal at the beginning of January 1931, and contractors immediately began razing the site.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Godwin Construction Company was contracted in April 1931 to excavate the site and construct the building's foundations.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] A groundbreaking ceremony for the freight terminal, attended by New York State governor Franklin D.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Roosevelt, took place on April 30, 1931.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] That September, the Port Authority received bids for the construction of the building's superstructure; the Turner Construction Company submitted a low bid of $7.591 million.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Construction required 120,000 cubic yards of concrete, 65 miles of piping, and 12 million bricks, as well as 160,000 barrels of cement.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority also paid to widen the streets on all four sides.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Four hundred railroad managers were invited to inspect the new terminal on September 9, 1932.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] 1 was formally dedicated the next week, September 16, though the building was not at that time fully completed.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] At the time it was the largest building in New York City.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building ultimately cost $16 million; the superstructure alone cost $8 million to $9 million.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Shippers and consignees began using a 265,000-square-foot (24,600 m2) freight terminal on the basement and first floor on October 3, 1932.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Only the basement and ground story were open at the time; the upper stories, intended for light manufacturing, were not expected to be completed until the end of the year.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Real-estate experts cited Inland Terminal No.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] 1 as one of several developments that were contributing to the growth of businesses in Chelsea.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The final dedication of the building occurred on February 25, 1933, with a ceremony attended by Port Authority, New York City, and New York state officials.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] A banquet was held in one of the building's truck elevators to mark its dedication.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Tenants had begun moving into the upper stories even before the building's dedication.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] By the beginning of 1933, eight hundred shipping firms were using the terminal to ship outbound freight, while fifty shippers received inbound freight there.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Each railroad paid the Port Authority ten cents for every 1 short ton (0.89 long tons; 0.91 t) of freight handled at the terminal.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal was to be used by all shippers in Manhattan between Houston Street to the south and 23rd Street to the north.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] At the time of construction it was estimated to be capable of handling one-third of the 680,000 annual tons of less-than-carload freight at the port.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Among the terminal's tenants during the 1930s were the Woolworth Company, Rand McNally, the New York Trust Company, and offices of the Works Progress Administration.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority hired Caldwell, Garvan & Bettini in October 1933 to construct a lobby, stair, and foyer for Commerce Hall on the building's second floor.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Commerce Hall opened on December 8, 1933, with an exhibit of Ford Motor Company vehicles.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal saw early success in reducing truck traffic to and from the railheads.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] For instance, on May 25, 1936, 250 trucks brought cargo to the building that was consolidated into only 37 trucks to take to the ferry terminals.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Commerce Hall hosted the National Business Show for several years in the 1930s.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] By February 1938, all of the building's space had been rented, despite the ongoing Great Depression.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] After Commerce Hall was closed in 1938, the floor was converted to regular commercial use.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Board of Estimate approved an agreement in 1940, in which the Port Authority would make annual $60,000 payments in lieu of taxes on the building.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building remained 95 percent occupied at the time.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Its tenants during the early 1940s included Sears, Roebuck and Company, as well as a regional office for the Second Corps Area.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] In spite of a decline in freight traffic during World War II, the Port Authority retained a good credit rating and, by 1945, had drawn up plans for two new freight terminals in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority's 1949 report noted a significant decrease in freight handling at the building due to an overall shift in Manhattan from rail to trucks for transporting goods.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Around this time, the Port Authority constructed additional inland terminals intended for truck traffic: the New York Union Motor Truck Terminal in 1949 and the Newark Union Motor Truck Terminal in 1950.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority began erecting a helipad on the building's roof in November 1950, and the helipad opened on May 31, 1951.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] It was the site of an accident on July 13, 1955, when a Bell 47 helicopter operated by the Port Authority crashed shortly after take-off and fell, in flames, onto the fifteenth floor, where it became stuck.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The pilot and his only passenger survived with injuries.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The last of the railroad companies left the building in 1963.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The shipping and manufacturing industries in Chelsea declined significantly during the 1960s, as firms moved from the neighborhood to elsewhere in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building remained the Port Authority's headquarters until the agency moved to the new World Trade Center in 1973.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority sold 111 Eighth Avenue to Realopco Inc. – a company operated by brothers Sylvan Lawrence and Seymour Cohn, who also led the Sylvan Lawrence Company – for $24 million in July 1973.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The owners added a CCTV system, replaced existing manually operated elevators with 12 automatic elevators, and refurbished the lobby, and they received a $25 million mortgage from Chase Manhattan Bank.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building had a 40 percent vacancy rate in 1975, a figure that increased the next year to 50 percent.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] This was attributed to the decline of manufacturing in New York City and the ongoing national recession; in addition, several tenants had vacated large blocks of space, including Interstate Stores and Atlantic Department Stores.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Mayor Abraham Beame proposed that the vacant space be leased to garment manufacturers, but many garment firms were loath to relocate.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] After the Sorg Printing Company leased some of the vacant space, the occupancy rate increased to 75 percent by January 1977.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Occupancy had rebounded to 90 percent by 1979.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Following Lawrence's death in 1981, Seymour Cohn and Lawrence's widow Alice each acquired a 50 percent stake in 111 Eighth Avenue.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Cohn and Alice Lawrence were unable to agree on what to do with 111 Eighth Avenue and three other buildings, leading to a protracted legal struggle.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] During the 1980s and 1990s, the building attracted a number of a tenants in the computer industry, who were drawn by the large floor space.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] In addition, numerous companies had moved their back office operations to 111 Eighth Avenue by the early 1980s.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building was 80 percent occupied in 1992, with space renting at $8 to $18 per square foot ($86 to $194/m2).
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] By the late 1990s, the building was 87 percent occupied, and Sylvan Lawrence had leased out 200,000 square feet (19,000 m2) during the preceding year.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building's largest tenants at the time included Citibank, the New York State Insurance Fund, and Prudential Securities.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The massive building served as a dwindling warehouse and back-office outpost through the end of the 1990s.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Cohn and Alice Lawrence agreed to sell off 111 Eighth Avenue and Lawrence's other three buildings in 1997.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Blackacre Capital Group and Taconic Investment Partners agreed to acquire the four buildings in November 1997 for $387 million; the sale was finalized in January 1998.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic marketed 111 Eighth Avenue as a carrier hotel for the new booming internet business, as the building had high ceilings, large floor plates, multiple fiber-optic connections, and five times the electrical capacity that typical tenants required.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] This was coupled with the fashionable rise of the Chelsea neighborhood that surrounded it.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic began a $50 million renovation, replacing the building's wiring.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] One-third of the space was leased to telecommunications companies and another one-third to advertising agencies and internet companies.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The new occupants could afford higher rents than the old industrial tenants.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Although Taconic tried to screen potential telecommunications tenants by establishing strict net-worth requirements, so many companies expressed interest in the building that Taconic had stopped accepting new telecommunications tenants by late 1999.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Average rents had more than doubled during the preceding two years, from $18 to $46 per square foot ($190 to $500/m2).
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] A 70,000-square-foot (6,500 m2) cancer treatment center, designed by Gwathmey Siegel & Associates Architects and operated by St.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Vincent's Hospital, opened in the building the same year.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Eighth and Ninth Avenue lobbies were renovated in 2000 and 2004, respectively.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] During the Northeast blackout of 2003, the building was able to keep power on, thanks to an underground fuel tank and 37 generators.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] In 2006, the Atlantic Theater Company opened a 99-seat black box theater in the building, and Lifetime Entertainment Services became its first cable television tenant.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Google opened its largest engineering office outside of California in the building in 2006, leasing 300,000 square feet (28,000 m2) across three floors.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Google workspace was noted for its campus-like and playful atmosphere, with perks including free food and a game room; *The New York Times* described it as "a vision of a workplace utopia as conceived by rich, young, single engineers in Silicon Valley, transplanted to Manhattan".
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] In 2010, Google contracted to purchase the entire building from Taconic, in a deal reported to be worth around $1.8 billion, the biggest purchase of a U.S. office building of the year.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The deal was credited with helping revive the New York City commercial real estate market, which had slumped during the Great Recession.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] After the purchase, Google was the largest tenant, with 500,000 square feet (46,000 m2) of the building.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic continued to manage the building under contract from Google.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Since its acquisition, the building has become popularly known as the "Google Building", and it is regarded as the company's East Coast headquarters.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] 111 Eighth Avenue is adjacent to trunk fiber optic lines stretching from Hudson Street and continuing up Ninth Avenue.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] That line at the time was owned by Lexent Metro Connect.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] There was speculation at the time of the acquisition that Google would use its strategic location to launch a Google Fiber operation in New York City.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Google Fiber plan never came to pass, and Google has denied it has any plans to bring it to New York City anytime in the near future, although in 2013 it did begin offering free Wi-Fi to its Chelsea neighbors.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The Lexent dark fiber line has been acquired by Lightower Fiber Networks.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] The building's meet-me room in its carrier hotel was one of the main network interconnections in the city as of 2006.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] In 2013 the first class of the newly created Cornell NYC Tech school began classes in the building, in space donated by Google.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Classes continued in the building until the school moved to its new location on Roosevelt Island in 2017.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Despite the massive size of the acquisition, Google has still found itself having to rent space elsewhere because it has been unable to break the leases with some of its tenants, including Nike, Deutsch Inc., and Bank of New York.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] After years of renting additional space across the street in the Chelsea Market, Google purchased that building in 2018.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] Google's expansion in Chelsea helped attract other technology companies to the area and contributed to gentrification.
[src:cornell-university/111-eighth-avenue] *The New York Times* described Google as drawing "relatively few complaints" in the neighborhood, and New York City Council speaker Corey Johnson called the company "a good neighbor", although some residents blamed it for changing the neighborhood's character and driving out smaller businesses.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A major worldwide financial crisis centered in the United States took place in 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The causes included excessive speculation on property values by both homeowners and financial institutions, leading to the 2000s United States housing bubble.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was exacerbated by predatory lending for subprime mortgages and by deficiencies in regulation.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Cash out refinancings had fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The first phase of the crisis was the subprime mortgage crisis, which began in early 2007, as mortgage-backed securities (MBS) tied to U.S. real estate, and a vast web of derivatives linked to those MBS collapsed in value.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A liquidity crisis spread to global institutions by mid-2007 and climaxed with the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers in September 2008, which triggered a stock market crash and bank runs in several countries.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in late-2007, as well as the United States bear market of 2007–2009.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was also a contributor to the 2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis and the euro area crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As the Federal Reserve ("Fed") lowered the federal funds rate from 2000 to 2003, institutions increasingly targeted low-income homebuyers, largely belonging to racial minorities, with high-risk loans; this development went unattended by regulators.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As interest rates rose from 2004 to 2006, the cost of mortgages rose and the demand for housing fell; in early 2007, as more U.S. subprime mortgage holders began defaulting on their repayments, lenders went bankrupt, culminating in the bankruptcy of New Century Financial in April.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As demand and prices continued to fall, the financial contagion spread to global credit markets by August 2007, and central banks began injecting liquidity.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In March 2008, Bear Stearns, the fifth-largest U.S. investment bank, was sold to JPMorgan Chase in a "fire sale" backed by Fed financing.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In response to the growing crisis, governments around the world deployed massive bailouts of financial institutions and used monetary policy and fiscal policies to prevent an economic collapse of the global financial system.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] By July 2008, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, companies which together owned or guaranteed half of the U.S. housing market, verged on collapse; the Housing and Economic Recovery Act of 2008 enabled the federal government to seize them on September 7.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] On October 3, Congress passed the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, authorizing the Treasury Department to purchase toxic assets and bank stocks through the $700 billion Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Fed began a program of quantitative easing by buying treasury bonds and other assets, such as MBS, and the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act, signed in February 2009 by newly elected president Barack Obama, included a range of measures intended to preserve existing jobs and create new ones.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] These initiatives combined, coupled with actions taken in other countries, ended the worst of the Great Recession by mid-2009.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Assessments of the crisis's impact in the U.S. vary, but suggest that some 8.7 million jobs were lost, causing unemployment to rise from 5% in 2007 to a high of 10% in October 2009.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The percentage of citizens living in poverty rose from 12.5% in 2007 to 15.1% in 2010.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by 53% between October 2007 and March 2009, and some estimates suggest that one in four households lost 75% or more of their net worth.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was passed, overhauling financial regulations.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was opposed by many Republicans, and it was weakened by the Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act in 2018.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were also adopted by countries around the world.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in mid-2007.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was among the five worst financial crises the world had experienced and led to a loss of more than $2 trillion from the global economy.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 (~$15 trillion in 2024) trillion.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The increase in cash out refinancings, as home values rose, fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many financial institutions owned investments whose value was based on home mortgages such as mortgage-backed securities, or credit derivatives used to insure them against failure, which declined in value significantly.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The International Monetary Fund estimated that large U.S. and European banks lost more than $1 trillion on toxic assets and from bad loans from January 2007 to September 2009.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Lack of investor confidence in bank solvency and declines in credit availability led to plummeting stock and commodity prices in late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis rapidly spread into a global economic shock, resulting in several bank failures.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Economies worldwide slowed during this period since credit tightened and international trade declined.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Housing markets suffered and unemployment soared, resulting in evictions and foreclosures.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] From its peak in the second quarter of 2007 at $61.4 trillion, household wealth in the United States fell $11 trillion, to $50.4 trillion by the end of the first quarter of 2009, resulting in a decline in consumption, then a decline in business investment.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the fourth quarter of 2008, the quarter-over-quarter decline in real GDP in the U.S. was 8.4%.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The U.S. unemployment rate peaked at 11.0% in October 2009, the highest rate since 1983 and roughly twice the pre-crisis rate.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The average hours per work week declined to 33, the lowest level since the government began collecting the data in 1964.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The economic crisis started in the U.S. but spread to the rest of the world.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. consumption accounted for more than a third of the growth in global consumption between 2000 and 2007 and the rest of the world depended on the U.S. consumer as a source of demand.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Toxic securities were owned by corporate and institutional investors globally.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Derivatives such as credit default swaps also increased the linkage between large financial institutions.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The de-leveraging of financial institutions, as assets were sold to pay back obligations that could not be refinanced in frozen credit markets, further accelerated the solvency crisis and caused a decrease in international trade.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Reductions in the growth rates of developing countries were due to falls in trade, commodity prices, investment and remittances sent from migrant workers (example: Armenia).
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] States with fragile political systems feared that investors from Western states would withdraw their money because of the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In effect, the central banks went from being the "lender of last resort" to the "lender of only resort" for a significant portion of the economy.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In some cases the Fed was considered the "buyer of last resort".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] During the fourth quarter of 2008, these central banks purchased US$2.5 trillion (~$3.57 trillion in 2024) of government debt and troubled private assets from banks.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was the largest liquidity injection into the credit market, and the largest monetary policy action in world history.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve created then-significant amounts of new currency as a method to combat the liquidity trap.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Bailouts came in the form of trillions of dollars of loans, asset purchases, guarantees, and direct spending.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Significant controversy accompanied the bailouts, such as in the case of the AIG bonus payments controversy, leading to the development of a variety of "decision making frameworks", to help balance competing policy interests during times of financial crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Alistair Darling, the U.K.'s Chancellor of the Exchequer at the time of the crisis, stated in 2018 that Britain came within hours of "a breakdown of law and order" the day that Royal Bank of Scotland was bailed-out.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Instead of financing more domestic loans, some banks instead spent some of the stimulus money in more profitable areas such as investing in emerging markets and foreign currencies.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In July 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was enacted in the United States to "promote the financial stability of the United States".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were adopted worldwide.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Since the 2008 financial crisis, consumer regulators in America have more closely supervised sellers of credit cards and home mortgages in order to deter anticompetitive practices that led to the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] At least two major reports on the causes of the crisis were produced by the U.S.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Congress: the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission report, released January 2011, and a report by the United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations entitled Wall Street and the Financial Crisis: Anatomy of a Financial Collapse, released April 2011.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In total, 47 bankers served jail time as a result of the crisis, over half of whom were from Iceland, where the crisis was the most severe and led to the collapse of all three major Icelandic banks.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In April 2012, Geir Haarde of Iceland became the only politician to be convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the aftermath of the crisis, U.S. authorities intensified enforcement actions against financial misconduct, including high-profile insider trading prosecutions such as that of Raj Rajaratnam, who was convicted in 2011.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Only one banker in the United States served jail time as a result of the crisis, Kareem Serageldin, a banker at Credit Suisse who was sentenced to 30 months in jail and returned $24.6 million in compensation for manipulating bond prices to hide $1 billion of losses.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] No individuals in the United Kingdom were convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Goldman Sachs*, Goldman Sachs paid a $550 million civil penalty and acknowledged that its marketing materials for CDO contained incomplete information, settling securities fraud charges after allegedly anticipating the financial crisis and selling toxic investments to its clients.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] With fewer resources to risk in creative destruction, the number of patent applications was flat, compared to exponential increases in patent application in prior years.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Typical American families did not fare well, nor did the "wealthy-but-not-wealthiest" families just beneath the pyramid's top.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, half of the poorest families in the United States did not have wealth declines at all during the crisis because they generally did not own financial investments whose value could fluctuate.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve surveyed 4,000 households from 2007 to 2009, and found that the total wealth of 63% of all Americans declined in that period and 77% of the richest families had a decrease in total wealth, while only 50% of those on the bottom of the pyramid suffered a decrease.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The following is a timeline of the major events of the financial crisis, including government responses, and the subsequent economic recovery.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the table, the names of emerging and developing economies are shown in boldface type, while the names of developed economies are in Roman (regular) type.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The expansion of central bank lending in response to the crisis was not confined to the Federal Reserve's provision of aid to individual financial institutions.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve has also conducted several innovative lending programs to improve liquidity and strengthen different financial institutions and markets, such as Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In this case, the major problem in the market is the lack of free cash reserves and flows to secure the loans.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve took many steps to deal with financial market liquidity worries.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] One of these steps was a credit line for major traders, who act as the Fed's partners in open market activities.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, loan programs were set up to make the money market mutual funds and commercial paper market more flexible.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility (TALF) was put in place thanks to a joint effort with the US Department of the Treasury.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This plan made it easier for consumers and businesses to get credit by giving Americans who owned high-quality asset-backed securities more credit.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Before the crisis, the Federal Reserve's stocks of Treasury securities were sold to pay for the increase in credit.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This method was meant to keep banks from trying to give out their extra savings, which could cause the federal funds rate to drop below where it was supposed to be.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, in October 2008, the Federal Reserve was granted the power to provide banks with interest payments on their surplus reserves.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This created a motivation for banks to retain their reserves instead of disbursing them, thus reducing the need for the Federal Reserve to hedge its increased lending by decreases in alternative assets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Money market funds also went through runs when people lost faith in the market.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] To keep it from getting worse, the Fed said it would give money to mutual fund companies.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Department of Treasury said that it would briefly cover the assets of the fund.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Both of these things helped get the fund market back to normal, which helped the commercial paper market, which most businesses use to run.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The FDIC also did several things, such as raising the insurance cap from $100,000 to $250,000, to boost customer trust.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] They engaged in quantitative easing, which added more than $4 trillion to the financial system and got banks to start lending again, both to each other and to people.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many homeowners who were trying to keep their homes from going into default got housing credits.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A package of policies was passed that let borrowers refinance their loans even though the value of their homes was less than what they still owed on their mortgages.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The relaxing of credit lending standards by investment banks and commercial banks allowed for a significant increase in subprime lending.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime had not become less risky; Wall Street just accepted this higher risk.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Due to competition between mortgage lenders for revenue and market share, and when the supply of creditworthy borrowers was limited, mortgage lenders relaxed underwriting standards and originated riskier mortgages to less creditworthy borrowers.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the view of some analysts, the relatively conservative government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) policed mortgage originators and maintained relatively high underwriting standards prior to 2003.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] However, as market power shifted from securitizers to originators, and as intense competition from private securitizers undermined GSE power, mortgage standards declined and risky loans proliferated.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The riskiest loans were originated in 2004–2007, the years of the most intense competition between securitizers and the lowest market share for the GSEs.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The GSEs eventually relaxed their standards to try to catch up with the private banks.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Depending on how "subprime" mortgages are defined, they remained below 10% of all mortgage originations until 2004, when they rose to nearly 20% and remained there through the 2005–2006 peak of the United States housing bubble.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Although they concede that governmental policies had some role in causing the crisis, they contend that GSE loans performed better than loans securitized by private investment banks, and performed better than some loans originated by institutions that held loans in their own portfolios.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In his dissent to the majority report of the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, conservative American Enterprise Institute fellow Peter J.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Based upon information in the SEC's December 2011 securities fraud case against six former executives of Fannie and Freddie, Peter Wallison and Edward Pinto estimated that, in 2008, Fannie and Freddie held 13 million substandard loans totaling over $2 trillion.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the early and mid-2000s, the Bush administration called numerous times for investigations into the safety and soundness of the GSEs and their swelling portfolio of subprime mortgages.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The hearings never resulted in new legislation or formal investigation of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, as many of the committee members refused to accept the report and instead rebuked OFHEO for their attempt at regulation.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Some, such as Wallison, believe this was an early warning to the systemic risk that the growing market in subprime mortgages posed to the U.S. financial system that went unheeded.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Sub-prime loans made by CRA-covered institutions constituted a 3% market share of LMI loans in 1998, but in the run-up to the crisis, fully 25% of all subprime lending occurred at CRA-covered institutions and another 25% of subprime loans had some connection with CRA.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] To other analysts the delay between CRA rule changes in 1995 and the explosion of subprime lending is not surprising, and does not exonerate the CRA.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They contend that there were two, connected causes to the crisis: the relaxation of underwriting standards in 1995 and the ultra-low interest rates initiated by the Federal Reserve after the terrorist attack on September 11, 2001.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Both causes had to be in place before the crisis could take place.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Critics also point out that publicly announced CRA loan commitments were massive, totaling $4.5 trillion in the years between 1994 and 2007.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They also argue that the Federal Reserve's classification of CRA loans as "prime" is based on the faulty and self-serving assumption that high-interest-rate loans (3 percentage points over average) equal "subprime" loans.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Others have pointed out that there were not enough of these loans made to cause a crisis of this magnitude.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By March 2011, the FDIC had paid out $9 billion (c. $12.3 billion in 2024) to cover losses on bad loans at 165 failed financial institutions.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Congressional Budget Office estimated, in June 2011, that the bailout to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac exceeds $300 billion (c. $411 billion in 2024) (calculated by adding the fair value deficits of the entities to the direct bailout funds at the time).
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other words, bubbles in both markets developed even though only the residential market was affected by these potential causes.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] *residential housing* bubble (as opposed to other types of bubbles) led to financial crisis was that it was supported by a huge number of substandard loans—generally with low or no downpayments.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Krugman's contention (that the growth of a commercial real estate bubble indicates that U.S. housing policy was not the cause of the crisis) is challenged by additional analysis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After researching the default of commercial loans during the financial crisis, Xudong An and Anthony B.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Business journalist Kimberly Amadeo reported: "The first signs of decline in residential real estate occurred in 2006.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Three years later, commercial real estate started feeling the effects." Denice A.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Between 1998 and 2006, the price of the typical American house increased by 124%.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During the 1980s and 1990s, the national median home price ranged from 2.9 to 3.1 times median household income.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By contrast, this ratio increased to 4.0 in 2004, and 4.6 in 2006.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This housing bubble resulted in many homeowners refinancing their homes at lower interest rates, or financing consumer spending by taking out second mortgages secured by the price appreciation.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In a Peabody Award-winning program, NPR correspondents argued that a "Giant Pool of Money" (represented by $70 trillion in worldwide fixed income investments) sought higher yields than those offered by U.S.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This pool of money had roughly doubled in size from 2000 to 2007, yet the supply of relatively safe, income generating investments had not grown as fast.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Investment banks on Wall Street answered this demand with products such as the mortgage-backed security and the collateralized debt obligation that were assigned safe ratings by the credit rating agencies.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In effect, Wall Street connected this pool of money to the mortgage market in the US, with enormous fees accruing to those throughout the mortgage supply chain, from the mortgage broker selling the loans to small banks that funded the brokers and the large investment banks behind them.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By approximately 2003, the supply of mortgages originated at traditional lending standards had been exhausted, and continued strong demand began to drive down lending standards.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The collateralized debt obligation in particular enabled financial institutions to obtain investor funds to finance subprime and other lending, extending or increasing the housing bubble and generating large fees.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This essentially places cash payments from multiple mortgages or other debt obligations into a single pool from which specific securities draw in a specific sequence of priority.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Those securities first in line received investment-grade ratings from rating agencies.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Securities with lower priority had lower credit ratings but theoretically a higher rate of return on the amount invested.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2008, average U.S. housing prices had declined by over 20% from their mid-2006 peak.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As prices declined, borrowers with adjustable-rate mortgages could not refinance to avoid the higher payments associated with rising interest rates and began to default.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During 2007, lenders began foreclosure proceedings on nearly 1.3 million properties, a 79% increase over 2006.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased to 2.3 million in 2008, an 81% increase vs.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By August 2008, approximately 9% of all U.S. mortgages outstanding were either delinquent or in foreclosure.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2009, this had risen to 14.4%.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After the bubble burst, Australian economist John Quiggin wrote: "And, unlike the Great Depression, this crisis was entirely the product of financial markets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Lower interest rates encouraged borrowing.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] From 2000 to 2003, the Federal Reserve lowered the federal funds rate target from 6.5% to 1.0%.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This was done to soften the effects of the collapse of the dot-com bubble and the September 11 attacks, as well as to combat a perceived risk of deflation.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As early as 2002, it was apparent that credit was fueling housing instead of business investment as some economists went so far as to advocate that the Fed "needs to create a housing bubble to replace the Nasdaq bubble".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, empirical studies using data from advanced countries show that excessive credit growth contributed greatly to the severity of the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Additional downward pressure on interest rates was created by a growing U.S. current account deficit, which peaked along with the housing bubble in 2006.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke explained how trade deficits required the U.S. to borrow money from abroad, in the process bidding up bond prices and lowering interest rates.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bernanke explained that between 1996 and 2004, the U.S. current account deficit increased by $650 billion, from 1.5% to 5.8% of GDP.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financing these deficits required the country to borrow large sums from abroad, much of it from countries running trade surpluses.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] These were mainly the emerging economies in Asia and oil-exporting nations.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The balance of payments identity requires that a country (such as the US) running a current account deficit also have a capital account (investment) surplus of the same amount.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Hence large and growing amounts of foreign funds (capital) flowed into the U.S. to finance its imports.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] All of this created demand for various types of financial assets, raising the prices of those assets while lowering interest rates.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign investors had these funds to lend either because they had very high personal savings rates (as high as 40% in China) or because of high oil prices.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Ben Bernanke referred to this as a "saving glut".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A flood of funds (capital or liquidity) reached the U.S. financial markets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign governments supplied funds by purchasing Treasury bonds and thus avoided much of the direct effect of the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households used funds borrowed from foreigners to finance consumption or to bid up the prices of housing and financial assets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financial institutions invested foreign funds in mortgage-backed securities.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Fed then raised the Fed funds rate significantly between July 2004 and July 2006.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This contributed to an increase in one-year and five-year adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) rates, making ARM interest rate resets more expensive for homeowners.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This may have also contributed to the deflation of the housing bubble, as asset prices generally move inversely to interest rates.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] It became riskier to speculate in housing.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. housing and financial assets dramatically declined in value after the housing bubble burst.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime lending standards declined in the U.S.: in early 2000, a subprime borrower had a FICO score of 660 or less.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By 2005, many lenders dropped the required FICO score to 620, making it much easier to qualify for prime loans and making subprime lending a riskier business.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Proof of income and assets were de-emphasized.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Loans at first required full documentation, then low documentation, then no documentation.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] One subprime mortgage product that gained wide acceptance was the no income, no job, no asset verification required (NINJA) mortgage.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Informally, these loans were aptly referred to as "liar loans" because they encouraged borrowers to be less than honest in the loan application process.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Testimony given to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission by whistleblower Richard M.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bowen III on events during his tenure as the Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup, where he was responsible for over 220 professional underwriters, suggests that by 2006 and 2007, the collapse of mortgage underwriting standards was endemic.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] His testimony stated that by 2006, 60% of mortgages purchased by Citigroup from some 1,600 mortgage companies were "defective" (were not underwritten to policy, or did not contain all policy-required documents).
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This, despite the fact that each of these 1,600 originators was contractually responsible (certified via representations and warrantees) that its mortgage originations met Citigroup standards.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, during 2007, "defective mortgages (from mortgage originators contractually bound to perform underwriting to Citi's standards) increased to over 80% of production".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The analysis, conducted on behalf of 23 investment and commercial banks, including 7 "too big to fail" banks, additionally showed that 28% of the sampled loans did not meet the minimal standards of any issuer.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Clayton's analysis further showed that 39% of these loans (i.e. those not meeting *any* issuer's minimal underwriting standards) were subsequently securitized and sold to investors.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Predatory lending refers to the practice of unscrupulous lenders enticing borrowers to enter into unfair or abusive secured loans for inappropriate purposes.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In May 2009, Bank of America modified 64,000 Countrywide loans as a result.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] When housing prices decreased, homeowners in ARMs then had little incentive to pay their monthly payments, since their home equity had disappeared.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This caused Countrywide's financial condition to deteriorate, ultimately resulting in a decision by the Office of Thrift Supervision to seize the lender.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Former employees from Ameriquest, which was the United States' leading wholesale lender, described a system in which they were pushed to falsify mortgage documents and then sell the mortgages to Wall Street banks eager to make fast profits.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] There is growing evidence that such mortgage frauds may be a cause of the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] According to Barry Eichengreen, the roots of the financial crisis lay in the deregulation of financial markets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A 2012 OECD study suggested that bank regulation based on the Basel accords encouraged unconventional business practices and contributed to or reinforced the financial crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other cases, laws were changed or enforcement weakened in parts of the financial system.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Prior to the crisis, financial institutions became highly leveraged, increasing their appetite for risky investments and reducing their resilience in case of losses.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Much of this leverage was achieved using complex financial instruments such as off-balance sheet securitization and derivatives, which made it difficult for creditors and regulators to monitor and try to reduce financial institution risk levels.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households and financial institutions became increasingly indebted or overleveraged during the years preceding the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased their vulnerability to the collapse of the housing bubble and worsened the ensuing economic downturn.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Free cash used by consumers from home equity extraction doubled from $627 billion in 2001 to $1,428 billion in 2005 as the housing bubble built, a total of nearly $5 trillion over the period, contributing to economic growth worldwide.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 trillion (c. $15 trillion in 2024).
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. household debt as a percentage of annual disposable personal income was 127% at the end of 2007, versus 77% in 1990.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1981, U.S. private debt was 123% of GDP; by the third quarter of 2008, it was 290%.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From 2004 to 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks each significantly increased their financial leverage, which increased their vulnerability to a financial shock.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Changes in capital requirements, intended to keep U.S. banks competitive with their European counterparts, allowed lower *risk weightings* for AAA-rated securities.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The shift from first-loss tranches to AAA-rated tranches was seen by regulators as a risk reduction that compensated the higher leverage.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These five institutions reported over $4.1 trillion in debt for fiscal year 2007, about 30% of U.S. nominal GDP for 2007.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Lehman Brothers went bankrupt and was liquidated, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became commercial banks, subjecting themselves to more stringent regulation.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With the exception of Lehman, these companies required or received government support.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, two U.S. government-sponsored enterprises, owned or guaranteed nearly $5 trillion (c. $7.13 trillion in 2024) trillion in mortgage obligations at the time they were placed into conservatorship by the U.S. government in September 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These seven entities were highly leveraged and had $9 trillion in debt or guarantee obligations; yet they were not subject to the same regulation as depository banks.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Behavior that may be optimal for an individual, such as saving more during adverse economic conditions, can be detrimental if too many individuals pursue the same behavior, as ultimately one person's consumption is another person's income.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Too many consumers attempting to save or pay down debt simultaneously is called the paradox of thrift and can cause or deepen a recession.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Hyman Minsky also described a "paradox of deleveraging" as financial institutions that have too much leverage (debt relative to equity) cannot all de-leverage simultaneously without significant declines in the value of their assets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The term financial innovation refers to the ongoing development of financial products designed to achieve particular client objectives, such as offsetting a particular risk exposure (such as the default of a borrower) or to assist with obtaining financing.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The usage of these products expanded dramatically in the years leading up to the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These products vary in complexity and the ease with which they can be valued on the books of financial institutions.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] CDO issuance grew from an estimated $20 billion in Q1 2004 to its peak of over $180 billion by Q1 2007, then declined back under $20 billion by Q1 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, the credit quality of CDO's declined from 2000 to 2007, as the level of subprime and other non-prime mortgage debt increased from 5% to 36% of CDO assets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As described in the section on subprime lending, the CDS and portfolio of CDS called synthetic CDO enabled a theoretically infinite amount to be wagered on the finite value of housing loans outstanding, provided that buyers and sellers of the derivatives could be found.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, buying a CDS to insure a CDO ended up giving the seller the same risk as if they owned the CDO, when those CDO's became worthless.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This boom in innovative financial products went hand in hand with more complexity.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] It multiplied the number of actors connected to a single mortgage (including mortgage brokers, specialized originators, the securitizers and their due diligence firms, managing agents and trading desks, and finally investors, insurances and providers of repo funding).
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Instead of spreading risk this provided the ground for fraudulent acts, misjudgments and finally market collapse.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists have studied the crisis as an instance of cascades in financial networks, where institutions' instability destabilized other institutions and led to knock-on effects.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Mortgage risks were underestimated by almost all institutions in the chain from originator to investor by underweighting the possibility of falling housing prices based on historical trends of the past 50 years.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While financial derivatives and structured products helped partition and shift risk between financial participants, it was the underestimation of falling housing prices and the resultant losses that led to aggregate risk.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For a variety of reasons, market participants did not accurately measure the risk inherent with financial innovation such as MBS and CDOs or understand its effect on the overall stability of the financial system.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The pricing model for CDOs clearly did not reflect the level of risk they introduced into the system.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] AIG insured obligations of various financial institutions through the usage of credit default swaps.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The basic CDS transaction involved AIG receiving a premium in exchange for a promise to pay money to party A in the event party B defaulted.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] However, AIG did not have the financial strength to support its many CDS commitments as the crisis progressed and was taken over by the government in September 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. taxpayers provided over $180 billion in government loans and investments in AIG during 2008 and early 2009, through which the money flowed to various counterparties to CDS transactions, including many large global financial institutions.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission (FCIC) made the major government study of the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The limitations of a widely used financial model also were not properly understood.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This formula assumed that the price of CDS was correlated with and could predict the correct price of mortgage-backed securities.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Because it was highly tractable, it rapidly came to be used by a huge percentage of CDO and CDS investors, issuers, and rating agencies.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As financial assets became more complex and harder to value, investors were reassured by the fact that the international bond rating agencies and bank regulators accepted as valid some complex mathematical models that showed the risks were much smaller than they actually were.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] George Soros commented that "The super-boom got out of hand when the new products became so complicated that the authorities could no longer calculate the risks and started relying on the risk management methods of the banks themselves.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Similarly, the rating agencies relied on the information provided by the originators of synthetic products.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A conflict of interest between investment management professional and institutional investors, combined with a global glut in investment capital, led to bad investments by asset managers in over-priced credit assets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Professional investment managers generally are compensated based on the volume of client assets under management.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is, therefore, an incentive for asset managers to expand their assets under management in order to maximize their compensation.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As the glut in global investment capital caused the yields on credit assets to decline, asset managers were faced with the choice of either investing in assets where returns did not reflect true credit risk or returning funds to clients.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Many asset managers continued to invest client funds in over-priced (under-yielding) investments, to the detriment of their clients, so they could maintain their assets under management.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] They supported this choice with a "plausible deniability" of the risks associated with subprime-based credit assets because the loss experience with early "vintages" of subprime loans was so low.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the dominance of the above formula, there are documented attempts of the financial industry, occurring before the crisis, to address the formula limitations, specifically the lack of dependence dynamics and the poor representation of extreme events.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The volume *Credit Correlation: Life After Copulas*, published in 2007 by World Scientific, summarizes a 2006 conference held by Merrill Lynch in London where several practitioners attempted to propose models rectifying some of the copula limitations.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] See also the article by Donnelly and Embrechts and the book by Brigo, Pallavicini and Torresetti, that reports relevant warnings and research on CDOs appeared in 2006.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is strong evidence that the riskiest, worst performing mortgages were funded through the "shadow banking system" and that competition from the shadow banking system may have pressured more traditional institutions to lower their underwriting standards and originate riskier loans.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These entities became critical to the credit markets underpinning the financial system, but were not subject to the same regulatory controls.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, these entities were vulnerable because of asset–liability mismatch, meaning that they borrowed short-term in liquid markets to purchase long-term, illiquid and risky assets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that disruptions in credit markets would force them to engage in rapid deleveraging, selling their long-term assets at depressed prices.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Paul Krugman, laureate of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences, described the run on the shadow banking system as the "core of what happened" to cause the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He referred to this lack of controls as "malign neglect" and argued that regulation should have been imposed on all banking-like activity.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Without the ability to obtain investor funds in exchange for most types of mortgage-backed securities or asset-backed commercial paper, investment banks and other entities in the shadow banking system could not provide funds to mortgage firms and other corporations.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that nearly one-third of the U.S. lending mechanism was frozen and continued to be frozen into June 2009.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While traditional banks raised their lending standards, it was the collapse of the shadow banking system that was the primary cause of the reduction in funds available for borrowing.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Caballero, Emmanuel Farhi, and Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas argued that the financial crisis was attributable to "global asset scarcity, which led to large capital flows toward the United States and to the creation of asset bubbles that eventually burst".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Long-only commodity index funds became popular – by one estimate investment increased from $90 billion in 2006 to $200 billion at the end of 2007, while commodity prices increased 71% – which raised concern as to whether these index funds caused the commodity bubble.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cause of the global asset bubble can be partially attributable to the global savings glut.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As theorized by Andrew Metrick, the demand for safe assets following the Asian Financial Crisis coupled with the lack of circulating treasuries created an unmet demand for "risk free" assets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Thus, institutional investors like sovereign wealth funds and pension funds began purchasing synthetic safe assets like Triple-A Mortgage Backed Securities.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As a consequence, the demand for so-called safe assets fueled the free flow of capital into housing in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This greatly worsened the crisis as banks and other financial institutions were incentivized to issue more mortgages than before.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Some commentators and economists associated with the Austrian School of economics, including former U.S.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Congressman Ron Paul and historian Tom Woods, have offered a libertarian interpretation of the crisis which differs from the explanations centered on deregulation and government oversight.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Ron Paul's book, *End the Fed,* Paul argues that the Federal Reserve's prolonged policy of artificially low interest rates in the early 2000s created a credit bubble that allowed for speculative investments and unsustainable levels of debt, particularly in housing.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Tom Woods' book *Meltdown*, he also contends that Federal Reserve manipulation of the money supply and credit markets distorted normal price signals, leading to widespread malinvestment, resulting in an inevitable correction.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Paul and Woods also criticized Fannie Mae's and Freddie Mac's role in the crisis, asserting that the entities engaged in excessive risk-taking by expanding homeownership beyond sustainable levels.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In doing this, the government intervention created moral hazard by assuring large financial institutions that they would receive government support in times of crisis, which Paul and Woods believe encouraged riskier behavior.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 1998 book, John McMurtry suggested that a financial crisis is a systemic crisis of capitalism itself.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his 1978 book, *The Downfall of Capitalism and Communism*, Ravi Batra suggests that growing inequality of financial capitalism produces speculative bubbles that burst and result in depression and major political changes.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also suggested that a "demand gap" related to differing wage and productivity growth explains deficit and debt dynamics important to stock market developments.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] John Bellamy Foster, a political economy analyst and editor of the *Monthly Review*, believed that the decrease in GDP growth rates since the early 1970s is due to increasing market saturation.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Marxian economics followers Andrew Kliman, Michael Roberts, and Guglielmo Carchedi, in contradistinction to the *Monthly Review* school represented by Foster, pointed to capitalism's long-term tendency of the rate of profit to fall as the underlying cause of crises generally.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From this point of view, the problem was the inability of capital to grow or accumulate at sufficient rates through productive investment alone.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Low rates of profit in productive sectors led to speculative investment in riskier assets, where there was potential for greater return on investment.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The speculative frenzy of the late 1990s and 2000s was, in this view, a consequence of a rising organic composition of capital, expressed through the fall in the rate of profit.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to Michael Roberts, the fall in the rate of profit "eventually triggered the credit crunch of 2007 when credit could no longer support profits".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005 book, *The Battle for the Soul of Capitalism*, John C.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Bogle wrote that "Corporate America went astray largely because the power of managers went virtually unchecked by our gatekeepers for far too long".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his book *The Big Mo*, Mark Roeder, a former executive at the Swiss-based UBS Bank, suggested that large-scale momentum, or The Big Mo, "played a pivotal role" in the financial crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Roeder suggested that "recent technological advances, such as computer-driven trading programs, together with the increasingly interconnected nature of markets, has magnified the momentum effect.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Robert Reich attributed the economic downturn to the stagnation of wages in the United States, particularly those of the hourly workers who comprise 80% of the workforce.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This stagnation forced the population to borrow to meet the cost of living.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists Ailsa McKay and Margunn Bjørnholt argued that the financial crisis and the response to it revealed a crisis of ideas in mainstream economics and within the economics profession, and call for a reshaping of both the economy, economic theory and the economics profession.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A report by the International Labour Organization concluded that cooperative banking institutions were less likely to fail than their competitors during the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cooperative banking sector had 20% market share of the European banking sector, but accounted for only 7% of all the write-downs and losses between the third quarter of 2007 and first quarter of 2011.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2008, in the U.S., the rate of commercial bank failures was almost triple that of credit unions, and almost five times the credit union rate in 2010.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Credit unions increased their lending to small- and medium-sized businesses while overall lending to those businesses decreased.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists, particularly followers of mainstream economics, mostly failed to predict the crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several followers of heterodox economics predicted the crisis, with varying arguments.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dirk Bezemer credits 12 economists with predicting the crisis: Dean Baker, Wynne Godley, Fred Harrison, Michael Hudson, Eric Janszen, Med Jones, Steve Keen, Jakob Broechner Madsen & Jens Kjaer Sørensen, Kurt Richebächer, Nouriel Roubini, Peter Schiff, and Robert Shiller.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Shiller, a founder of the Case–Shiller index that measures home prices, wrote an article a year before the collapse of Lehman Brothers in which he predicted that a slowing U.S. housing market would cause the housing bubble to burst, leading to financial collapse.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Peter Schiff regularly appeared on television in the years before the crisis and warned of the impending real estate collapse.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Austrian School regarded the crisis as a vindication and classic example of a predictable credit-fueled bubble caused by laxity in monetary supply.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There were other economists that did warn of a pending crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The former Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, Raghuram Rajan, had predicted the crisis in 2005 when he became chief economist at the International Monetary Fund.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005, at a celebration honoring Alan Greenspan, who was about to retire as chairman of the US Federal Reserve, Rajan delivered a controversial paper that was critical of the financial sector.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In that paper, Rajan "argued that disaster might loom".
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Rajan argued that financial sector managers were encouraged to "take risks that generate severe adverse consequences with small probability but, in return, offer generous compensation the rest of the time.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also took action against the establishment view by making a big financial bet on banking stocks and making a fortune from the crisis ("They didn't listen, so I took their money").
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Popular articles published in the mass media have led the general public to believe that the majority of economists have failed in their obligation to predict the financial crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, an article in *The New York Times* noted that economist Nouriel Roubini warned of such crisis as early as September 2006, and stated that the profession of economics is bad at predicting recessions.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to *The Guardian*, Roubini was ridiculed for predicting a collapse of the housing market and worldwide recession, while *The New York Times* labelled him "Dr.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 2012 article in the journal *Japan and the World Economy*, Andrew K.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Spiegel used a Multiple Indicator Multiple Cause (MIMIC) model on a cross-section of 107 countries to evaluate potential causes of the 2008 crisis.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The authors examined various economic indicators, ignoring contagion effects across countries.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the fact that we use a wide number of possible causes in a flexible statistical framework, we are unable to link most of the commonly cited causes of the crisis to its incidence across countries.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The first visible institution to run into trouble in the United States was the Southern California–based IndyMac, a spin-off of Countrywide Financial.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Before its failure, IndyMac Bank was the largest savings and loan association in the Los Angeles market and the seventh-largest mortgage loan originator in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The failure of IndyMac Bank on July 11, 2008, was (until the crisis precipitated even larger failures) the fourth-largest bank failure in United States history, and the second-largest failure of a regulated thrift.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank's parent corporation was IndyMac Bancorp until the FDIC seized IndyMac Bank.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy in July 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank was founded as Countrywide Mortgage Investment in 1985 by David S.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Loeb and Angelo Mozilo as a means of collateralizing Countrywide Financial loans too big to be sold to Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1997, Countrywide spun off IndyMac as an independent company run by Mike Perry, who remained its CEO until the downfall of the bank in July 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The primary causes of its failure were largely associated with its business strategy of originating and securitizing Alt-A loans on a large scale.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This strategy resulted in rapid growth and a high concentration of risky assets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From its inception as a savings association in 2000, IndyMac grew to the seventh largest savings and loan and ninth largest originator of mortgage loans in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] During 2006, IndyMac originated over $90 billion (~$134 billion in 2024) of mortgages.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac often made loans without verification of the borrower's income or assets, and to borrowers with poor credit histories.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Appraisals obtained by IndyMac on underlying collateral were often questionable as well.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As an Alt-A lender, IndyMac's business model was to offer loan products to fit the borrower's needs, using an extensive array of risky option-adjustable-rate mortgages (option ARMs), subprime loans, 80/20 loans, and other nontraditional products.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Ultimately, loans were made to many borrowers who simply could not afford to make their payments.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The thrift remained profitable only as long as it was able to sell those loans in the secondary mortgage market.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac resisted efforts to regulate its involvement in those loans or tighten their issuing criteria: see the comment by Ruthann Melbourne, Chief Risk Officer, to the regulating agencies.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On May 12, 2008, in the "Capital" section of its last 10-Q, IndyMac revealed that it may not be well capitalized in the future.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that during April 2008, Moody's and Standard & Poor's downgraded the ratings on a significant number of Mortgage-backed security (MBS) bonds—including $160 million (~$228 million in 2024) issued by IndyMac that the bank retained in its MBS portfolio.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac concluded that these downgrades would have harmed its risk-based capital ratio as of June 30, 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Had these lowered ratings been in effect on March 31, 2008, IndyMac concluded that the bank's capital ratio would have been 9.27% total risk-based.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac warned that if its regulators found its capital position to have fallen below "well capitalized" (minimum 10% risk-based capital ratio) to "adequately capitalized" (8–10% risk-based capital ratio) the bank might no longer be able to use brokered deposits as a source of funds.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Senator Charles Schumer (D-NY) later pointed out that brokered deposits made up more than 37% of IndyMac's total deposits, and asked the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) whether it had considered ordering IndyMac to reduce its reliance on these deposits.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $18.9 billion in total deposits reported on March 31, Senator Schumer would have been referring to a little over $7 billion in brokered deposits.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the breakout of maturities of these deposits is not known exactly, a simple averaging would have put the threat of brokered deposits loss to IndyMac at $500 million a month, had the regulator disallowed IndyMac from acquiring new brokered deposits on June 30.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac was taking new measures to preserve capital, such as deferring interest payments on some preferred securities.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dividends on common shares had already been suspended for the first quarter of 2008, after being cut in half the previous quarter.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The company still had not secured a significant capital infusion nor found a ready buyer.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that the bank's risk-based capital was only $47 million above the minimum required for this 10% mark.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] But it did not reveal some of that $47 million (~$67 million in 2024) capital it claimed it had, as of March 31, 2008, was fabricated.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] When home prices declined in the latter half of 2007 and the secondary mortgage market collapsed, IndyMac was forced to hold $10.7 billion (~$15.5 billion in 2024) of loans it could not sell in the secondary market.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Its reduced liquidity was further exacerbated in late June 2008 when account holders withdrew $1.55 billion (~$2.21 billion in 2024) or about 7.5% of IndyMac's deposits.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This bank run on the thrift followed the public release of a letter from Senator Charles Schumer to the FDIC and OTS.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The letter outlined the Senator's concerns with IndyMac.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the run was a contributing factor in the timing of IndyMac's demise, the underlying cause of the failure was the unsafe and unsound way it was operated.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac announced the closure of both its retail lending and wholesale divisions, halted new loan submissions, and cut 3,800 jobs.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On July 11, 2008, citing liquidity concerns, the FDIC put IndyMac Bank into conservatorship.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A bridge bank, IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB, was established to assume control of IndyMac Bank's assets, its secured liabilities, and its insured deposit accounts.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC announced plans to open IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB on July 14, 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Until then, depositors would have access to their insured deposits through ATMs, their existing checks, and their existing debit cards.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Telephone and Internet account access was restored when the bank reopened.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC guarantees the funds of all insured accounts up to US$100,000, and declared a special advance dividend to the roughly 10,000 depositors with funds in excess of the insured amount, guaranteeing 50% of any amounts in excess of $100,000.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Yet, even with the pending sale of Indymac to IMB Management Holdings, an estimated 10,000 uninsured depositors of Indymac are still at a loss of over $270 million.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $32 billion in assets, IndyMac Bank was one of the largest bank failures in American history.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy on July 31, 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Initially the companies affected were those directly involved in home construction and mortgage lending such as Northern Rock and Countrywide Financial, as they could no longer obtain financing through the credit markets.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Over 100 mortgage lenders went bankrupt during 2007 and 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Concerns that investment bank Bear Stearns would collapse in March 2008 resulted in its fire-sale to JP Morgan Chase.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The financial institution crisis hit its peak in September and October 2008.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several major institutions either failed, were acquired under duress, or were subject to government takeover.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These included Lehman Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, Washington Mutual, Wachovia, Citigroup, and AIG.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On October 6, 2008, three weeks after Lehman Brothers filed the largest bankruptcy in U.S. history, Lehman's former CEO Richard S.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld Jr. found himself before Representative Henry A.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Waxman, the California Democrat who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform.
[src:cornell-university/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld said he was a victim of the collapse, blaming a "crisis of confidence" in the markets for dooming his firm.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] 26 Broadway is on a pentagonal site bounded by Broadway to the northwest, Bowling Green to the west, Beaver Street to the south, New Street to the east/southeast, and the axis of Morris Street to the north.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The first sixteen stories occupy much of the lot, with several setbacks, a curved facade along Broadway, and two light courts.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Above it is a twelve-story tower topped by a stepped pyramid.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The ground story has a 40-foot-tall (12 m) lobby leading to three banks of elevators.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Standard Oil executive offices on the top stories included a board room on the 21st floor.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The original structure was built for Standard Oil on the former site of U.S. treasury secretary Alexander Hamilton's house.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Standard Oil Building was expanded in 1895 and again after World War I, when Walter C.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Teagle bought four neighboring buildings to create a continuous lot.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The building was greatly expanded in a multi-phase construction project during the 1920s.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] 26 Broadway was sold to another owner in 1956 but remained a prominent structure on Bowling Green.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In 1995, the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designated 26 Broadway as an official city landmark.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] It is also a contributing property to the Wall Street Historic District, a National Register of Historic Places district created in 2007.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Standard Oil Building is at 26 Broadway in the Financial District of Lower Manhattan in New York City.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] It is bounded by Broadway to the northwest and west (along Bowling Green), Beaver Street to the south, and New Street to the east and southeast.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] It occupies the physical lots of 10-30 Broadway, 1-11 Beaver Street, and 73-81 New Street.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The building has a land lot with an area of 46,055 square feet (4,278.6 m2).
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The site has a frontage of about 278 feet (85 m) along Broadway, 160 feet (49 m) along Beaver Street, and 204 feet (62 m) along New Street.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Nearby buildings include 2 Broadway to the south; 1 Broadway and the Alexander Hamilton U.S.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Custom House to the southwest; and the *Charging Bull* sculpture, Bowling Green Offices Building, and the Cunard Building (25 Broadway) to the west.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In addition, 70 Broad Street is one block southeast.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The New York City Subway's Whitehall Street station (served by the R and W trains) and Bowling Green station (served by the 4 and 5 trains) are both less than a block south.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Standard Oil Building was one of several corporate headquarters to be constructed at the southern end of Broadway during the early 20th century.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The building was designed by Thomas Hastings of Carrère and Hastings, in conjunction with Shreve, Lamb & Blake, in the Renaissance Revival style.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] It was the only skyscraper that Carrère and Hastings designed in Lower Manhattan.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Richmond Shreve of Shreve, Lamb & Blake oversaw the construction of the building's expansion and was tasked with solving logistical issues; however, not much is known about the tasks performed by William F.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The structure is 520 feet (160 m) tall, and it is cited as containing either 31 or 34 stories.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The building was erected by general contractor C.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Wills Inc. and structural steel contractor Post & McCord.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Numerous other contractors and engineers were involved in the building's construction.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Its lower portion occupies the entire pentagonal lot, following the curving contour of Broadway at that point, while its tower is aligned with the grid to which Lower Manhattan's other skyscrapers conform.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A deep light court measuring 45 by 85 feet (14 by 26 m) cuts through the center of the Beaver Street facade; an interior light court measuring 25 by 90 feet (7.6 by 27.4 m) is also present on the northern side of the building.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Beaver Street light court was the last section to be constructed due to the presence of a holdout lot occupied by Childs Restaurants.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The original Standard Oil Building, a 15- or 16-story building initially faced in brick, still exists at the base of the modern skyscraper.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The interior floors of the annex portions were designed so that they were at the same level as the floors in the original building.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The newer floors are carried by trusses over the original structure, rather than resting on the older building's walls.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In total, the base of the building is 16 stories.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] 26 Broadway features numerous setbacks on its facade, as mandated by the 1916 Zoning Resolution.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The lowest such setback is at the 10th floor on the New and Beaver Streets sides, and another setback exists on all side above the 16th floor, where the building's base transitions into the tower.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The tower section of 26 Broadway contains an additional 13 stories above the northern edge of the expanded base, above which is a stepped triple-height pyramid.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Two other setbacks exist above the 18th and 22nd floors of the tower.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The setbacks give the tower a dimension of 82 by 142 feet (25 by 43 m) at the 17th and 18th stories, tapering to 80 feet (24 m) square above the 22nd story.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The modern building's facade is primarily composed of buff-colored Indiana Limestone, covering the tower and much of the base.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The limestone facade at the lowest four stories is rusticated.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The original building's facade was made of red brick and granite, making it appear as though the original section was separate from the expanded structure.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Part of this facade is visible from New Street, but the Broadway facade was totally replaced with limestone.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A small portion of the original building's southern facade is still visible but was given a limestone overlay.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Broadway facade slopes slightly downward to the south: at the northern part of the building, the ground level is at the same height as the building's second floor.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] It is designed so the first and fourth floors have rows of openings, while the second and third floors have some large arched windows.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The main entrance is near the middle of the curved Broadway facade; it consists of a recessed double-height arch, with elaborately carved spandrels at its top.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Double-height arched windows are on either side of the main entrance arch.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] There are also two secondary entrances at 24 and 28 Broadway, respectively to the south and north of the main arch; these entrances are within doorways topped by pediments and clocks.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The former was historically an entrance to retail space, while the latter provides access to the original building.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In the southern section of the Broadway facade, as well as on the wings facing Beaver Street, the arched windows are flanked by smaller windows.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] On Beaver Street to the south, the ground level is at the same elevation as the first floor and contains storefronts.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Beaver Street facade is divided into three sections.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The center section only reaches to the third floor and contains a cornice above projecting vertical pilasters, while the taller outer sections contain double-height arched windows between smaller window openings.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] On New Street, the facade is divided into two sections: the northern section is made of brick and granite, and the southern section is made of limestone.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Above the base, the Broadway facade rises as a twelve-story wall resembling a cliff; it is interrupted only by a setback from the Beaver Street side, where there is an intermediate cornice.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The bays around each corner and around the center arch has quoins from the fourth to the 12th stories.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The 13th story is designed as an intermediate cornice, while the 14th through 16th stories (the top three floors of the base) are designed as a colonnade.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] There are minor differences in decoration related to when each part of the facade was built.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The 14th through 16th stories have shallow pilasters on the newer northern portion of the Broadway facade, while the older southern portion has engaged Ionic columns.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The tower section of the building rises 13 or 14 stories from the base.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The 22nd-story setback has obelisks at each corner.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The three highest stories of the tower are surrounded by a colonnade with Ionic columns.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The tower is topped by a ziggurat-style pyramid that was inspired by the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The pyramid was added when the building was expanded in the 1920s, with its finial rising 480 feet (150 m) above ground level.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] It serves not only as a steam vent but also as an allusion to the Greek god Hephaestus.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The pyramid contains a cauldron that initially was lit by four kerosene lamps; this signified the fact that Standard Oil's founders, the Rockefeller family, made their first profits from kerosene.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The cauldron's light was extinguished after 1956.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The modern building was constructed in several phases around the preexisting buildings.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The buildings were occupied by numerous tenants, who were allowed to temporarily stay in place due to the dearth of office space in Lower Manhattan in the 1920s.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The original Standard Oil structure was on the northern boundary of the site.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Further complicating work was the presence of quicksand some 15 to 18 feet (4.6 to 5.5 m) below ground, underneath which was a hardpan of clay, gravel, and boulders.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Tide water ranged from 12 to 37 feet (3.7 to 11.3 m) beneath the ground, under which was another layer of shale and earth 15 to 20 feet (4.6 to 6.1 m) deep; the underlying bedrock was under the shale and earth.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Welles Building and the original Standard Oil Building contained thick footings that went into the quicksand, though only a few of the footings reached the hardpan.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Thus, the water had to be pumped out of the site before the superstructure was built.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The new footings were built using a caisson method.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A cofferdam wall was built underneath part of the expanded site, extending down to the bedrock at the deepest level.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A complex system of underpinning was then undertaken so that the existing buildings would not collapse while excavation and construction of the foundation was ongoing.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The building contains a basement 10 feet (3.0 m) deep, as well as a sub-basement 37 feet (11 m) deep, the latter of which contains all of 26 Broadway's mechanical equipment.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The entrance hall is 40 feet (12 m) high.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] It is finished with pink marble and contains pairs of Corinthian marble pilasters, carrying a marble cornice with the names of Standard Oil's cofounders.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Above the cornice is a beamed ceiling and decorative panels with signs of the zodiac.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In addition, the floors are clad in travertine and black marble, and the walls have bronze grilles.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Lighting fixtures, doors, and gates are also made of wrought iron with bronze ornamentation.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The use of columns, pilasters, rusticated walls, and heavy staircases and doorways was intended to create the effect of "a princely palace or merchant's mansion".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Leading off the lobby are three banks of elevators: two on the south side of the main corridor, as well as a set of four elevators on the east side near New Street.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Fifteen elevators serve only the first through 16th stories, while six serve the tower's executive offices, for a total of 21 passenger elevators.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A set of three fire stairs also rises the height of the building.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] When the building was completed, each story also had its own fire alarm station and watchman's tower, as well as bronze-framed directory signs.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] On the lowest sixteen stories, a hallway typically leads from the elevators around the interior light court, and there is office space both around the interior light court and the exterior boundary.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The tower floors have L-shaped corridors.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Access to the older southern portion of the building is provided from the newer northern portion on all stories, with fire doors connecting both portions.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The walls of the elevator foyers have Botticino marble paneling reaching to the ceiling, and the main hallways have 5-foot-tall (1.5 m) marble wainscoting.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The floors in the main foyers and corridors are designed with Tennessee marble bordered with black marble, while the white-plastered ceilings each contain a molding with dentils.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In the side corridors, the walls are finished in hard plaster and have 5-foot-tall (1.5 m) hollow metal moldings.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The side corridors have hollow-metal trim and doors with mahogany finishes, as well as gray-and-buff flooring strips.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The executive stories contained oak-paneled offices, as well as reception rooms and meeting rooms.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] These spaces were designed by the firm of Clinton & Russell, Holton & George.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The 17th story had space for an executive dining room, with space for nearly 200 people, and an adjoining kitchen.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The dining space had tile floors and 7-foot-tall (2.1 m) tile wainscoting; white-enamel screens and enclosures; and a refrigerator with an ice machine.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The 21st floor housed Standard Oil successor Socony's board room, which overlooked Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The boardroom covered 2,000 square feet (190 m2) and contained a double-height ceiling with relief panels; a limestone fireplace; and oak wainscoting.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The oak panels on the ceiling beams, and the stone on the walls, were attached to the skyscraper's steel frame.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Next to it was an anteroom with carved oak pilasters, frieze, and moldings, as well as a plaster ceiling and Kato stone wall.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Private offices extended south and east of the 21st-story boardroom and had walnut walls, plaster ceilings, Siena marble fireplaces, and cork floors covered with carpets.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The 23rd floor contained squash courts with adjoining locker and shower rooms.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The site of the Standard Oil Building was occupied by Dutch houses after the colony of New Amsterdam was founded in the 17th century.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In the late 18th century, 26 Broadway was the home address of Alexander Hamilton, his wife Elizabeth Schuyler Hamilton, and their family.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Hamilton occupied the house after resigning his position as United States Secretary of the Treasury.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] According to a 1786 directory, rum was also sold from the address in the late 18th century.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Starting in the early 19th century, when New York City became a nationally prominent commercial hub, many firms chose to build their headquarters in Lower Manhattan, renting the unused space to subsidiaries or other companies.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Corporations sought addresses in the Financial District as status symbols.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Furthermore, many companies built their original headquarters in the 19th century and replaced these with larger structures in the early 20th century.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Standard Oil Trust moved its headquarters to New York City from Cleveland, Ohio, in 1870.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] By 1884, the company had acquired lots at 24-28 Broadway near Bowling Green, and had started erecting a headquarters building at the site.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Standard Oil Building, opened in 1885, was designed by architect Francis H.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Kimball as a nine-story, 86-foot-wide (26 m) building that extended between Broadway to the west and New Street to the east.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Roberts with a Renaissance Revival granite facade, and had a flat roof above the ninth floor, as well as a central bay that rose an additional story.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Initially, all of Standard Oil's 40 operations were controlled from 26 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A photograph that year showed that 26 Broadway was flanked by other buildings and was 16 stories high.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The structure measured 117 feet (36 m) along Broadway and 100 feet (30 m) along New Street with a depth of 203 feet (62 m).
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] By 1890, Standard Oil had controlled 88 percent of the refined oil flows in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In an attempt to avoid public scrutiny, in 1899 Standard Oil was reorganized as the Standard Oil Company of New Jersey, a holding company based at 26 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] This did not resolve the monopoly concerns: *The New York Times* in 1906 said that "every cent of [Standard Oil's subsidiaries] made found its way to 26 Broadway".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] United States* was decided in May 1911, Standard Oil was required to be broken up into several smaller firms.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] As a result of the decision, several subdivisions were forced to move, including Tenant Corn Refining Products Company and U.S.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] By December 1911, half of the company's divisions were still housed at 26 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The building ultimately served as the headquarters of the Standard Oil Company of New York (Socony, later Mobil) once the split was completed.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] After World War I, Standard Oil president Walter C.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Teagle decided to greatly expand the structure by buying the neighboring buildings on the block.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] At the time, the area around Bowling Green was quickly developing into a shipping center within Lower Manhattan.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Planning for an expansion began in 1918.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] To the north of the original Standard Oil Building was the 17-story Hudson Building, followed by a 21-story office building at 36-42 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Socony was reported to have purchased the latter in February 1920, paying $6 million and beating out two other bidders for the property.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The next month, the company acquired or leased all four structures that stood between the existing building and Beaver Street to the south.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] According to *The New York Times*, the brokers valued the $30 million transaction as "probably the largest real estate transaction ever closed in the city".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] After the acquisitions were complete, Socony had a total frontage of 500 feet (150 m) facing Broadway, not all of which were to be part of the headquarters' expansion.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] This frontage was truncated soon after, as Socony sold the Arcade at 44-50 Broadway in March 1920.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In August 1920, Carrère and Hastings filed plans with the New York City Department of Buildings for enlarging 26 Broadway to 24 stories, plus a three-story pyramidal roof.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The firm had previously conducted several commissions for several Socony partners.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Thomas Hastings—the only living partner of Carrère and Hastings, who had helped design the Cunard Building across the street—was chosen as lead architect.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Shreve, Lamb & Blake were named as the associated architects.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Further details of 26 Broadway's major expansion were publicly announced in March 1921.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The building was to cost $5 million and rise 480 feet (150 m), covering a lot of 40,000 square feet (3,700 m2), with a total floor area of 500,000 square feet (46,000 m2), thus becoming one of Lower Manhattan's "largest structures".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The project included replacement of the old building's Broadway facade.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The initial plans called for a small pavilion to be built atop the existing 16 stories.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Construction was complicated by the Childs Restaurants location's decision to hold out until its lease expired; the difficulty of evicting the four buildings' occupants; and a dearth of available office space in the neighborhood.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] As a result, the expansion was undertaken in four phases, and the plans were changed in 1921 to allow for a light court around the location of the restaurant, rather than a bulky base as first projected.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The headquarters was also built with provisions for internal partitions so the leased portions of the building could be separated if the landowners ever wanted their property back when the lease expired.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The existing buildings on the site were underpinned so that existing tenants could remain until construction started on these respective sections.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Work started in 1921 at the southeastern corner of the site, at Beaver and New Streets, on the site of the Lisbon Building.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The section at the southwestern corner, the former Produce Exchange Bank at Broadway and Beaver Street, began two years later.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Two tenants could not relocate before the construction was scheduled to start, so engineers began demolishing one building while underpinning the neighboring structure.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Welles Building on Broadway began to be demolished around 1922.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The original building's brick facade on Broadway was replaced in 1924–1925, but the facade along New Street was kept in place.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The last section of the site to be built was the lot occupied by Childs Restaurants, which was not developed until 1928, after the restaurant's lease had run out.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Marshall Construction Company was hired to modify the building in 1929.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] 26 Broadway was known as the "Rockefeller address" because the offices of John D.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Rockefeller Jr. and John Sr. were in the building.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Jo Davidson had sculpted a bust of the junior Rockefeller, which had been installed in the skyscraper's lobby in 1925.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Parker Chase in 1932, "many of the great firms of the nation" were headquartered at 26 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] After the construction of Rockefeller Center, the offices of both Rockefellers moved to 30 Rockefeller Plaza in 1933.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The same year, Standard Oil of New Jersey (by that time, also known phonetically as Esso) announced its intention to consolidate its operations at Rockefeller Center, although it retained other offices at 26 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] National Fuel Gas also moved to Rockefeller Center in 1936, and Esso moved its remaining offices to 75 Rockefeller Plaza in 1946.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Socony, which had merged in 1931 with Vacuum Oil to form Socony-Vacuum, retained its headquarters in 26 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Socony-Vacuum started using coal to heat the building in 1941, conserving about 12,000 barrels of oil per year.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Socony-Vacuum moved some of its offices back to 26 Broadway in 1947 after Esso had vacated the space.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The structure was renamed the Socony-Vacuum Building in 1950.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Socony-Vacuum moved to 150 East 42nd Street in 1954 and placed for sale the next year.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The building was sold to the firm of Koeppel & Koeppel in February 1956.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] By that May, two-thirds of the building's space had already been leased to tenants such as Anaconda Copper and First National City Bank.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Standard & Poor's leased spaces at 25 and 26 Broadway starting in the late 1970s.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Museum of American Finance (MOAF) was founded in the building in 1988, initially occupying 250 square feet (23 m2) of space on the ground floor.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Koeppel's Independence Partners purchased the building for $16 million the following year.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In 1995, 26 Broadway and several other buildings on Bowling Green were formally designated as New York City landmarks.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In 2007, the building was designated as a contributing property to the Wall Street Historic District, a National Register of Historic Places district.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] S&P started leasing space at nearby 55 Water Street in 1997, vacating its former quarters at 25 and 26 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Standard & Poor's moved out in late 1999, and the vacant space was completely filled by the following April.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The ownership of the building and the underlying plots remained separate until 2007, when the Chetrit Group bought the building and two of the three lots underneath for $225 million.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Chetrit bought the remaining leasehold for $34.93 million in 2010; the lease had been held by the estate of Elmer Ellsworth Smathers, who had signed a 99-year lease in 1920.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] As of 2019, 26 Broadway is owned by Broadway 26 Waterview, while Chetrit Group is landlord for many of the interior spaces, and Newmark Group is the landlord's broker.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The subsequent years also saw the departure or closure of several tenants.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The MOAF opened a gallery at the building's 24 Broadway entrance in 1992, which was moved to the 28 Broadway entrance in 1996, and the entire museum finally relocated to 48 Wall Street in 2006.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Sports Museum of America opened within the building in 2008, but the museum quickly went into debt because of low patronage, and it closed in 2009.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Additionally, Dowling College Manhattan was in the Standard Oil Building until it closed in 2016.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] By 2026, the Chetrit Group had fallen behind on $330 million in loans that had been placed on the building.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] As of 2025, tenants include Cornell University's College of Architecture, Art, and Planning, Olo, SecondMarket, SpeechCycle, and JDRF.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The New York Film Academy leased the entire 12th floor in 2014.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Other tenants include the coworking company Primary, the law firm Schlam Stone & Dolan, and the design company Ustwo Studio.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The largest tenant of 26 Broadway is the New York City Department of Education (NYCDOE), and the building contains numerous schools and offices administered by the NYCDOE.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The Lower Manhattan Community School, a middle school, serves grades 6–8.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A second middle school, the New York City Charter School of the Arts, also serves grades 6-8 and moved into the building in 2018.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A third, the Urban Assembly School of Business for Young Women, is a high school serving grades 9–12, which had been founded in 2005.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In addition, the New York City School Construction Authority leases the fourth through sixth floors, taking up 288,000 square feet (26,800 m2).
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The New York State Court of Claims maintains four courtrooms and Chambers for its New York City District Judges in 26 Broadway.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Originally located in the World Trade Center, the Court of Claims moved into a 20,000-square-foot (1,900 m2) space at 26 Broadway after the World Trade Center was destroyed in the September 11 attacks.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] A writer for *The New York Times* praised the building plans in 1922, saying that the expanded building would be a "landmark in the city skyline".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] As the building was completed, architectural critics praised the design of 26 Broadway as having more emphasis on its form instead of the articulation of windows and other details.
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Blackall, for instance, stated that the building's specialty was in its massing, with the windows and other details as "incidents".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] The British architect Charles Herbert Reilly said that "the combination possible of stepped building and tower", as used in 26 Broadway, could contribute to a form "more interesting even than that of the Woolworth Building".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] When the building was completed, Charles Downing Lay called the building "a new point of interest in [New York City's] famous skyline".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Parker Chase focused on the detail, describing the entrance as welcoming and the lobby and corridor as "plain and simple".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] In a book about the work of Carrère and Hastings, Mark Hewitt wrote that 26 Broadway was "one of the supreme accomplishments of American Classicism".
[src:cornell-university/26-broadway] Gerard Wolfe, in his 1994 book *New York, a Guide to the Metropolis*, wrote that the building "formed an integral part of the lovely New York skyline" prior to the proliferation of post–World War II office buildings.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The **Aalto University School of Business** (Finnish: *Aalto-yliopiston kauppakorkeakoulu*; Swedish: *Aalto-universitets handelshögskola*) is the largest business school in Finland.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Founded in 1911, it is the second oldest business school in Finland and one of the oldest business schools in the Nordic countries.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The school became part of Aalto University on 1 January 2010.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] It has been previously known as the **Helsinki School of Economics**, the **Helsinki School of Economics and Business Administration**, and during 2010–2012 the **Aalto University School of Economics**.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The Aalto University School of Business is the first business school in the Nordic countries to have received the Triple Crown accreditation (accreditations from the three largest and most influential business school accreditation organizations: AACSB, AMBA, and EQUIS).
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] In terms of admissions, the school is considered the most difficult business school in Finland.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] In 2019, the school had the highest number of applicants for any higher education program in Finland.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] It also had the lowest acceptance rate of any business school in the country.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The Aalto University School of Business was established in Helsinki in 1904 by the business community and was given the status of a university in 1911.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] It operated as a private university until 1974 when the state of Finland was given the financial responsibility of the university.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Nevertheless, the school has remained autonomous in its administration and internal affairs.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Since its founding, 23,000 students have graduated.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] In 1950, the School of Business moved from Fabianinkatu to Runeberginkatu in Töölö.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The school became a part of Aalto University on 1 January 2010 and fully transitioned to its Otaniemi campus in 2019.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The Aalto University School of Business has been accredited by all three major international organizations that certify business schools (AACSB, AMBA, EQUIS), a triple-crown accreditation possessed by only 55 other universities in the world.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The school is also a member of the CEMS (Global Alliance in Management Education) and PIM (Partnership in International Management).
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Since 2005, the *Financial Times* has ranked the CEMS program among the top masters in management programs in the world.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The Aalto University School of Business is an active member of this joint program.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The *Financial Times* ranked the Aalto University School of Business 29th in the European business school rankings in 2013, 78th in Global MBA programs, and 43rd in Master in Management programs.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The school offers university degrees in economics and business administration at the bachelor's, master's, licentiate, and doctoral levels, along with MBA programmes targeted to business professionals hosted through Aalto University Executive Education.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The school has a two-step program structure, accordingly to the Bologna Treaty, with a three-year bachelor's degree followed by a two-year master's degree.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] New students start by studying towards a BSc degree in economics and business administration and on completion, are eligible to continue to study for the master's degree.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] A doctoral degree normally takes four additional years.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Since 1995, the school has offered a multidisciplinary summer programme called the Information Technology Program (3-month programme, 24 ECTS credits).
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The school also offers a multidisciplinary Business Master Class summer course (2-week course, 6 ECTS credits).
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] MBA and executive MBA programs are offered by the Aalto University Executive Education AEE with operations in Helsinki, China, Singapore, South Korea, Taiwan, Sweden and Iran.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] There is a tuition fee in the MBA program, unlike in the BSc/MSc degree programs.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Each year, around 400 students are admitted into the bachelor's programmes and around 200 students to the master's programmes.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Bachelor's admissions are based mainly on an admissions test (in Finnish) and the nationwide matriculation examination.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Non-Finnish speakers and international students have the opportunity to gain admission through the SAT (Scholastic Admissions Test) conducted in English.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Applicants with an appropriate bachelor's degree may apply for the master's admission to taking only the degree of Master of Science in economics and business administration.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The Aalto University School of Business has exchange partnerships with over 150 universities on six different continents.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Each year, close to 400 students go abroad on their exchange and the school welcomes over 350 incoming exchange students.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The school collaborates with the leading business schools in Europe within the CEMS community.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] In the CEMS network, partner schools include HEC Paris in France, ESADE in Spain, the London School of Economics in the UK and the University of St.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The CEMS includes 30 academic institutions from 5 continents, over 70 corporate partners and 4 social partners from around the globe.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The Aalto University School of Business has been a Finnish member of the CEMS network since 1998.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Their CEMS corporate partners are Kone and Nokia.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Most of the CEMS MIM elements are fully incorporated in the Global Management master's programme (120 ECTS).
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] CEMS MIM has high recognition in the corporate sector.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] Consistently ranked among the top in the world by the Financial Times, the CEMS MIM unites multinational companies and international-calibre professors from leading universities and business schools.
[src:cornell-university/aalto-university-school-of-business] The School of Business is a member of the PIM Network, which consists of 60 business schools worldwide.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] An **academic library** is a library that is attached to a higher education institution, which supports the curriculum and the research of the university faculty and students.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] According to the National Center for Education Statistics, there are an estimated 3,700 academic libraries in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Class reading materials, intended to supplement lectures by the instructor and housed in academic libraries, have historically been known as "reserves".
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Before electronic resources became available, the reserves were supplied as actual books or as photocopies of appropriate journal articles.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Modern academic libraries provide access to electronic resources.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic libraries must determine a focus for collection development since comprehensive collections are not feasible.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Librarians do this by identifying the needs of the faculty, student body, the mission and academic programs of the college or university.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] When there are particular areas of specialization in academic libraries, these are often referred to as niche collections.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] These collections are often the basis of a special collection department and they may include original papers, manuscripts, artwork, and artifacts written or created by a single author or about a specific subject.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] There is a great deal of variation among academic libraries based on their size, resources, collections, and services.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The Harvard Library, which houses over 20 million volumes, is the largest strictly academic library in the world, although the Danish Royal Library—a combined national and academic library—has a larger collection at about 37 million volumes.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The University of California operates the largest academic library system in the world, managing about 41 million volumes across 100 libraries on ten campuses.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Another notable example is the University of the South Pacific which has academic libraries distributed throughout its twelve member countries.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Libraries date back to the ancient world.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The earliest academic libraries include the Library of Alexandria and the library at Nalanda University, which apparently burned for months because of the sheer number of manuscripts.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The first colleges in the United States were largely intended to train clergy members.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The libraries associated with these institutions largely consisted of donated books on the subjects of theology and the classics.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] In 1766, Harvard University had the most volumes held followed by Yale University, which had 4,000 volumes.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Access to these libraries was restricted to faculty members and a few students: the only staff was a part-time faculty member or the president of the college.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The priority of the library was to protect the books, not to allow patrons to use them.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] In 1849, Yale was open 30 hours a week, the University of Virginia was open nine hours a week, Columbia University four, and Bowdoin College only three.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Students instead created literary societies and assessed entrance fees for building a small collection of usable volumes, often over what the university library held.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] In 1876, the American Library Association (ALA) was formed with members including Melvil Dewey and Charles Ammi Cutter.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Libraries re-prioritized to improve access to materials and found funding increasing due to increased demand for said materials.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] In 1904, the Bibliographical Society of America was founded to foster the study of books and manuscripts.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic librarians were the majority of members.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic libraries today vary regarding the extent to which they accommodate those not affiliated with their parent universities.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Some offer reading and borrowing privileges to members of the public on payment of an annual fee; such fees can vary greatly.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The benefits usually do not extend to such services as computer usage other than to search the catalog or Internet access.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Alumni and students of cooperating local universities may be given discounts or other considerations when arranging for borrowing privileges.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] On the other hand, some universities' libraries are restricted to students, faculty, and staff.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Even in this case, they may make it possible for others to borrow materials through interlibrary loan programs.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Libraries of land-grant universities generally are more accessible to the public.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] In some cases, they are official government document repositories and are required to be open to the public.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Still, public members are generally charged fees for borrowing privileges and usually are not allowed to access everything they would be able to as students.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Harvard Library at Harvard University, a private Ivy League university in Cambridge, Massachusetts, is the largest academic library in the world with over 20 million volumes, 400 million manuscripts, 10 million photographs, and one million maps.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] In Canada, academic libraries have been more recently developed than in other nations.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The first academic library in Canada, opened in 1789, was in Windsor, Nova Scotia, at the University of King's College.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic libraries were significantly small during the 19th century and up until the 1950s, when Canadian academic libraries began to grow steadily as a result of greater importance being placed on education and research.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] In the 1960s, academic libraries in Canada began to grow as a direct result of larger student enrollments, increased graduate programs, higher budget allowance, and general advocacy of the importance of these libraries.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] As a result of this growth and the Ontario New Universities Library Project that occurred during the early 1960s, five new universities were established in Ontario that all included fully cataloged collections.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The establishment of libraries was widespread throughout Canada and was furthered by grants provided by the Canada Council and the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council, which sought to enhance library collections.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Since many academic libraries were constructed after World War II, a majority of the Canadian academic libraries that were built before 1940 that had not been updated to modern lighting, air conditioning, etc., are either no longer in use or are on the verge of decline.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The total number of college and university libraries increased from 31 in 1959–1960 to 105 in 1969–1970.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Following the growth of academic libraries in Canada during the 1960s, there was a brief period of sedation, which directly resulted from some significant budgetary issues.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] These academic libraries were faced with cost issues relating to the recently developed service of interlibrary lending and the high costs of periodicals on acquisition budgets, which affected overall acquisition budgeting and ultimately public collections.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Canadian academic libraries faced consistent problems relating to insufficient supplies and an overall lack of coordination among collections.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic libraries within Canada might not have flourished or continued to be strengthened without the help of outside organizations.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The Ontario Council of University Libraries (OCUL) was established in 1967 to promote unity among Canadian academic libraries.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] The Ontario College and University Library Association (OCULA) is attached to the Ontario Library Association (OLA) and is concerned with representing academic librarians regarding issues shared in the academic library setting.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Among the earliest academic libraries in Europe are Bodleian Library at the University of Oxford (founded in 1602), the Library of Trinity College Dublin (founded in 1592), and Vilnius University Library in Lithuania (founded in 1570).
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Unlike U.S. academic libraries, many academic libraries in Europe do not have open stacks like American academic libraries do, which can also apply to an institution's general collections.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Although some European academic libraries utilize a classification system similar to or based upon the Dewey Decimal Classification (DDC) used in the U.S., European academic libraries sometimes develop their own systems to organize their collections.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic libraries have transformed in the 21st century to focus less on physical collection development, information access, and digital resources.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Today's academic libraries typically provide access to subscription-based online resources, including research databases and ebook collections, in addition to physical books and journals.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic libraries also offer space for students to work and study, in groups or individually, on "silent floors" and reference and research help services, sometimes including virtual reference services.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Some academic libraries lend out technology such as video cameras, iPads, and calculators.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Many academic libraries have remodeled to reflect this changing focus as learning commons.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic libraries and learning commons often house tutoring, writing centers, and other academic services.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] A major focus of modern academic libraries is information literacy instruction, with most American academic libraries employing a person or department of people dedicated primarily to instruction.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Many academic institutions offer faculty status to librarians, and librarians are often expected to publish research in their field.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic librarian positions in the United States usually require an MLIS degree from an ALA-accredited institution.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Academic libraries are increasingly responsible for advancing open science practices.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Libraries support open access publishing through institutional repositories, transformative agreements, and assistance with article processing charges.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Many provide research data management services, including guidance on data sharing, metadata standards, and compliance with funder mandates.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] Libraries are also expanding into areas such as open educational resources (OER) and citizen science engagement.
[src:cornell-university/academic-library] This broadening role positions academic libraries as key facilitators in the transition toward more collaborative, inclusive, and sustainable models of scholarship.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ***Academic Ranking of World Universities*** (***ARWU***), also known as the **Shanghai Ranking**, is one of the annual publications of world university rankings.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The league table was originally compiled and issued by Shanghai Jiao Tong University in 2003, making it the first global university ranking with multifarious indicators.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Since 2009, *ARWU* has been published and copyrighted annually by Shanghai Ranking Consultancy, an organization focusing on higher education that is not legally subordinated to any universities or government agencies.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] In 2011, a board of international advisory consisting of scholars and policy researchers was established to provide suggestions.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The publication currently includes global league tables for institutions as a whole and for a selection of individual subjects, alongside independent regional *Greater China Ranking* and *Macedonian HEIs Ranking*.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Altbach named ARWU's 'consistency, clarity of purpose, and transparency' as significant strengths.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] University of Oxford Chancellor Chris Patten has said "the methodology looks fairly solid ... it looks like a pretty good stab at a fair comparison." While ARWU has originated in China, the ranking have been praised for being unbiased towards Asian institutions, especially Chinese institutions.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ranking has been criticised for "relying too much on award factors" thus undermining the importance of quality of instruction and humanities.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2007 paper published in the journal *Scientometrics* found that the results from the Shanghai rankings could not be reproduced from raw data using the method described by Liu and Cheng.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2013 paper in the same journal finally showed how the Shanghai ranking results could be reproduced.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Vincke analyse how the ARWU works, using their insights as specialists of Multiple Criteria Decision Making (MCDM).
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Their main conclusions are that the criteria used are not relevant; that the aggregation methodology has a number of major problems; and that insufficient attention has been paid to fundamental choices of criteria.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Cheng, think that the quality of universities cannot be precisely measured by mere numbers and any ranking must be controversial.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They suggest that university and college rankings should be used with caution and their methodologies must be understood clearly before reporting or using the results.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] *ARWU* has been criticised by the European Commission as well as some EU member states for "favour[ing] Anglo-Saxon higher education institutions".
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] For instance, *ARWU* is repeatedly criticised in France, where it triggers an annual controversy, focusing on its ill-adapted character to the French academic system and the unreasonable weight given to research often performed decades ago.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] It is also criticised in France for its use as a motivation for merging universities into larger ones.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Several methods for ranking universities were analyzed.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Many scholars proposed developing new methodologies for global university rankings, expressing concerns about bias against universities in the Arab region within current ranking systems.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They emphasized the need to adjust the weighting of indicators to account for overlooked institutional differences.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] There are two categories in *ARWU'*s disciplinary rankings: broad subject fields and specific subjects.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The methodology is similar to that adopted in the overall table, including award factors, paper citation, and the number of highly cited scholars.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Considering the development of specific areas, two independent regional league tables with different methodologies were launched – Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China and Best Chinese Universities Ranking.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Best Chinese Universities Ranking was first released in 2015.
[src:cornell-university/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China was first released in 2011.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The **ACT** (/ˈeɪ.ˌsiː.ˌtiː/ ⓘ, *AY-see-tee*; originally an abbreviation of **American College Testing**) is a standardized test used for college admissions in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] It is administered by ACT, Inc., a for-profit organization of the same name.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT test covers three academic skill areas: English, mathematics, and reading.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] It also offers optional scientific reasoning and direct writing tests.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] It is accepted by many four-year colleges and universities in the United States as well as more than 225 universities outside of the U.S.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The multiple-choice test sections of the ACT (all except the optional writing test) are individually scored on a scale of 1–36.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] In addition, a composite score consisting of the rounded whole number average of the scores for English, reading, and math is provided.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT was first introduced in November 1959 by University of Iowa professor Everett Franklin Lindquist as a competitor to the SAT.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT originally consisted of four tests: English, Mathematics, Social Studies, and Natural Sciences.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] In 1989, however, the Social Studies test was changed into a Reading section (which included a social sciences subsection), and the Natural Sciences test was renamed the Science Reasoning test, with more emphasis on problem-solving skills as opposed to memorizing scientific facts.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] In February 2005, an optional Writing Test was added to the ACT.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] By the fall of 2017, computer-based ACT tests were available for school-day testing in limited school districts of the US, with greater availability expected in fall of 2018.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] In July 2024, the ACT announced that the test duration was shortened; the science section, like the writing one, would become optional; and online testing would be rolled out nationally in spring 2025 and for school-day testing in spring 2026.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT has seen a gradual increase in the number of test takers since its inception, and in 2012 the ACT surpassed the SAT for the first time in total test takers; that year, 1,666,017 students took the ACT and 1,664,479 students took the SAT.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] On June 30th, 2026, ETS, the largest educational testing and assessment nonprofit, announced the acquisition of ACT.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] ACT, Inc., says that the ACT assessment measures high school students' general educational development and their capability to complete college-level work with the multiple choice tests covering four skill areas: English, mathematics, reading, and (optionally) science.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The optional Writing Test measures skill in planning and writing a short essay.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Specifically, ACT states that its scores provide an indicator of "college readiness", and that scores in each of the subtests correspond to skills in entry-level college courses in English, algebra, social science, humanities, and biology.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] According to a research study conducted by ACT, Inc. in 2003, there was a relationship between a student's ACT composite score and the probability of that student earning a college degree.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] To develop the test, ACT incorporates the objectives for instruction from middle and high schools throughout the United States, reviews approved textbooks for subjects taught in Grades 7–12, and surveys educators on which knowledge skills are relevant to success in postsecondary education.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] ACT publishes a technical manual that summarizes studies conducted on its validity in predicting freshman GPA, equating different high school GPAs, and measuring educational achievement.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] ACT scores are used to supplement the secondary school record and help admission officers put local data—such as coursework, grades, and class rank—in a national perspective.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The majority of colleges do not indicate a preference for the SAT or ACT exams and accept both, being treated equally by most admissions officers.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Most colleges use ACT scores as only one factor in the admission process.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] A sampling of ACT admissions scores shows that the 75th percentile composite score was 24.1 at public four-year institutions and 25.3 at private four-year institutions.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] In addition, some states and individual school districts have used the ACT to assess student learning and/or the performance of schools, requiring all high school students to take the ACT, regardless of whether they are college bound.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Colorado and Illinois were the first to incorporate the ACT as part of their mandatory testing program in 2001.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Other states followed suit in subsequent years.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] During the 2018–2019 school year, 13 states will administer the ACT test to all public school 11th graders, and another six states will fund ACT test administration as an option or choice for districts.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT is more widely used in the Midwestern, Rocky Mountain, and Southern United States, whereas the SAT is more popular on the East and West coasts.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Recently, however, the ACT is being used more on the East Coast.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Use of the ACT by colleges has risen as a result of various criticisms of the effectiveness and fairness of the SAT.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The required portion of the ACT is divided into three multiple-choice subject tests: English, mathematics, and reading.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Subject test scores, including the optional science section, range from 1 to 36; all scores are integers.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The English, mathematics, and reading tests also have subscores ranging from 1 to 18 (the subject score is not the sum of the subscores).
[src:cornell-university/act-test] In addition, students taking the optional writing test receive a writing score ranging from 2 to 12 (this is a change from the previous 1–36 score range); the optional science and writing scores do not affect the composite score.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Prior to September 2015, there was a Combined English/Writing score, which was a 36-point combination of the 36-point English Test score and the 12-point Writing subscore.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT has eliminated the Combined English/writing score and has added two new combined scores: ELA (an average of the English, Reading, and Writing scores) and STEM (an average of the Math and Science scores).
[src:cornell-university/act-test] These changes for the writing, ELA, and STEM scores were effective starting with the September 2015 test.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Each question answered correctly is worth one raw point, and there is no penalty for marking incorrect answers on the multiple-choice parts of the test; a student can answer all questions without a decrease in their score due to incorrect answers.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] This is parallel to several AP Tests eliminating the penalties for incorrect answers.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] To improve the result, students can retake the test: 55% of students who retake the ACT improve their scores, 22% score the same, and 23% see their scores decrease.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The first section is the 45-minute English test covering usage/mechanics, sentence structure, and rhetorical skills.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The 75-question test consists of five passages with various sections underlined on one side of the page and options to correct the underlined portions on the other side of the page.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The second section is a 60-minute, 60-question math test with the usual distribution of questions being approximately 14 covering pre-algebra, 10 elementary algebra, 9 intermediate algebra, 14 plane geometry, 9 coordinate geometry, and 4 elementary trigonometry questions.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] However, the distribution of question topics varies from test to test.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The difficulty of questions usually increases as a test taker moves on to higher question numbers.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Calculators are permitted in this section only.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Standard graphing calculators, such as the TI-83 and TI-84, are allowed.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Within the TI-Nspire family, the standard and CX versions are allowed while the CX CAS is not.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] As of April 2025 for online tests, and September 2025 for paper-and-pencil tests, each math question has four answer choices instead of five.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The reading section is a 35-minute, 40-question test that consists of four sections, three of which contain one long prose passage and one which contains two shorter prose passages.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The passages are representative of the levels and kinds of text commonly encountered in first-year college curriculum.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] This reading test assesses skills in three general categories: key ideas and details, craft and structure, and integration of knowledge and ideas.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Test questions will usually ask students to derive meaning from texts referring to what is explicitly stated or by reasoning to determine implicit meanings.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The optional science section is a 35-minute, 40-question test.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] There are seven passages each followed by five to seven questions.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The passages have three different formats: Data Representation, Research Summary, and Conflicting Viewpoints.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] But so far, there is still always only one Conflicting Viewpoints passage.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] These changes are very recent, and the only reference to them so far is in the recently released practice test on the ACT website.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The science section was mandatory until 2024, when it was made optional with the goal of giving students additional flexibility when taking the ACT exam.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The optional writing section, which is always administered at the end of the test, is 40 minutes (increasing from the original 30-minute time limit on the September 2015 test).
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The essay does not affect the composite score or the English section score; it is only given as a separate writing score and is included in the ELA score.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Two trained readers assign each essay subscores between 1 and 6 in four different categories: Ideas and Analysis, Development and Support, Organization, Language Use and Conventions.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Scores of 0 are reserved for essays that are blank, off-topic, non-English, not written with a no.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] 2 pencil, or considered illegible after several attempts at reading.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The subscores from the two different readers are summed to produce final domain scores from 2 to 12 (or 0) in each of the four categories.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] If the two readers' subscores differ by more than one point, then a senior third reader makes the final decision on the score.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The four domain scores are combined through a process that has not been described to create a writing section score between 1 and 36.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Note that the domain scores are not added to create the writing section score.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Although the writing section is optional, many colleges require an essay score and will factor it into the admissions decision (but fewer than half of all colleges have this requirement).
[src:cornell-university/act-test] For the "enhanced" version of the ACT introduced in 1989, the mean score of each of the four tests, as well as the mean composite score, was scaled to be 18, with an intended standard error of measurement of 2 for the four test scores and 1 for the composite score.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] These statistics vary from year to year for current populations of ACT takers.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The chart below summarizes each section and the average test score based on graduating high school seniors in 2025.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The table below summarizes how many students achieved a composite score of 36 on the ACT between the years of 1990 and 2025.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT Assessment Student Report, at ACT.org, provides the typical ACT Composite averages for college and universities admission policies.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] They caution that "because admission policies vary across colleges, the score ranges should be considered rough guidelines." Following is a list of the average composite scores that typically are accepted at colleges or universities.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT is offered seven times a year in the United States and its territories, Puerto Rico, and Canada: in September, October, December, February, April, June, and July.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] (In New York State, the test is not offered in July.) In other locations, the ACT is offered five times a year: in September, October, December, April, and June.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT is offered only on Saturdays except for those with credible religious obligations, who may take the test on another day.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT is designed, administered, and scored so that there is no advantage to testing on one particular date.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] For candidates in the United States, the ACT assessment costs $65.00 and there are two optional add-ons, the science section ($4.00) and the writing section ($25.00).
[src:cornell-university/act-test] For candidates outside of the United States, the test costs considerably more, at $186.50, with science costing $10.00, although writing retains its price of $25.00.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] For the 2025 testing dates, the science section is only optional for the digital test.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Students with verifiable disabilities, including physical and learning disabilities, are eligible to take the test with accommodations.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The standard time increase for students requiring additional time due to disabilities is 50%.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Originally, the score sheet was labeled that additional time was granted due to a learning disability; however, this was ultimately dropped because it was deemed illegal under the Americans with Disabilities Act and could be perceived as an unfair designator of disability.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Scores are sent to the student, their high school, and up to four colleges of the student's choice (optional).
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Time is a major factor to consider in testing.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The ACT is generally regarded as being composed of somewhat easier questions versus the SAT, but the shorter time allotted to complete each section increases difficulty.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Comparatively, the SAT is structured such that the test taker is allowed at least one minute per question, on generally shorter sections (25 or fewer questions).
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Times may be adjusted as a matter of accommodation for certain disabilities or other impairments.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Score reports provided to students taking the ACT test include the ranks (or cumulative percents) for each score and subscore received by the student.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Each rank gives the percentage of recently tested students in the U.S. who scored at or below the given student's score.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The following table shows the ACT national ranks as of the 2020-21 school year.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The College Board (the developer of the SAT) and ACT, Inc. compared scores from about 600,000 students who were graduating in 2017 and who took both the SAT (2016 revision) and the ACT in 2016 and 2017.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The following table shows, for each ACT composite score in the data set, the corresponding range of SAT total scores for students with the same percentile rank on each test.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The most appropriate corresponding SAT score point for the given ACT score is also shown in the table.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The data in this section pertains to the SAT prior to the 2016 redesign.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Comparisons to SAT scores are not valid after the 2017 graduating class.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Sixty percent—about 2.03 million students—of the 2017 high school graduating class took the ACT.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] For the graduating class of 2017, the average composite score was a 21.0.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] Of these test-takers, 46% were male and 52% were female, with 2% not reporting a gender.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] 2,760 students in the graduating class of 2017 received the highest ACT composite score of 36.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] The following chart shows, for each ACT score from 11 to 36, the corresponding ACT percentile and equivalent total SAT score or score range.
[src:cornell-university/act-test] (Concordance data for ACT scores less than 11 is not yet available for the current version of the SAT.) Note that ACT percentiles are defined as the percentage of test takers scoring at or below the given score.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university is organized into eight undergraduate colleges and seven graduate divisions on its main Ithaca campus.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Each college and academic division has near autonomy in defining its respective admission standards and academic curriculum.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In addition to its primary campus in Ithaca, Cornell University administers three satellite campuses, including two in New York City, the medical school and Cornell Tech, and a branch of the medical school in Al Rayyan in Education City, Qatar.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell is one of three private land-grant universities in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The main campus of Cornell University in Ithaca spans 745 acres (301 ha).
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of October 2024, 64 Nobel laureates, 4 Turing Award winners, and 1 Fields Medalist have been affiliated with Cornell University.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The institution counts more than 250,000 living alumni, which include 34 Marshall Scholars, 33 Rhodes Scholars, 29 Truman Scholars, 63 Olympic medalists, 10 current *Fortune* 500 CEOs, and 35 billionaires.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University was founded on April 27, 1865, by Ezra Cornell, an entrepreneur and New York State senator, and Andrew Dickson White, an educator and fellow state senator.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university was established as New York's land-grant institution following authorization by the New York State Legislature.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Ezra Cornell provided his farm in Ithaca, New York, as the initial campus site and contributed $500,000 as an initial endowment (equivalent to $13,074,000 in 2025).
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] White agreed to serve as the university's first president.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] White oversaw the university's early development, including construction of its first two buildings, and traveled to recruit students and faculty.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university was formally inaugurated on October 7, 1868, with 412 male students enrolling the following day.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell developed as a technologically innovative institution, incorporating academic research into campus infrastructure and outreach.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 1883, it became one of the first electrified universities, employing a water-powered dynamo to light parts of the campus.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Since 1894, the university has incorporated state-funded colleges that fulfill statutory requirements, and it administers research and extension programs jointly funded by New York State and the U.S. federal government.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 1872, Cornell became one of the first U.S. universities to allow alumni-elected trustees on its board.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Cornell was home to literary societies that promoted writing, reading, and oratory.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Bureau of Education classified several of these societies as following the traditions of literary organizations at Eastern universities.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 1967, Cornell experienced a fire in the Residential Club dormitory that killed eight students and one professor.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In the late 1960s, Cornell was among the Ivy League universities that experienced heightened student activism related to cultural issues, civil rights, and opposition to U.S. involvement in the Vietnam War.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 1969, armed anti–Vietnam War protesters occupied Willard Straight Hall, an incident that led to a restructuring of university governance and forced the resignation of then-president James Alfred Perkins.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University and its academic programs have routinely ranked among the best in the world.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 1995, the National Research Council ranked Cornell's Ph.D. programs sixth in the nation.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The council ranked Cornell's College of Arts and Humanities faculty fifth in the nation, its mathematics and physical sciences faculty sixth, and its College of Engineering fifth.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2000, Cornell began expanding its international programs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2004, the university opened Weill Cornell Medical College in Qatar in Education City in Al Rayyan, Qatar.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2020, Cornell admitted that it had failed to disclose close to $1.9 billion dollars in Qatari funding, according to Section 117 of the Higher Education Act.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2026 it was reported that Cornell received $2.3 billion from Qatar, out of a total of $3 billion from foreign nations.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university also developed partnerships with academic institutions in India, the China, and Singapore.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In August 2002, a graduate student group, At What Cost?, formed at Cornell to oppose a graduate student unionization drive run by CASE/UAW, an affiliate of the United Auto Workers.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The vote to unionize, held in October 2002, was rejected; At What Cost? was considered instrumental in the unusually large 90% turnout and the two-to-one defeat of the proposal, the first time a U.S. graduate school vote on unionization was defeated.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In March 2004, Cornell and Stanford University laid the cornerstone for the building and operation of the "Bridging the Rift Center," located on the border between Israel and Jordan, to be used for education.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Lehman, a former president of Cornell, described the university and its high international profile as a "transnational university".
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In November 2025, Cornell agreed to pay $30 million to the federal government and invest $30 million in agricultural research in order to restore $250 million in funding and settle investigations into campus antisemitism and DEI practices.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University's main campus is located in Ithaca, New York, on East Hill, offering views of the city and Cayuga Lake.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The campus has expanded to approximately 745 acres (301 ha) since its founding, now including multiple academic buildings, laboratories, administrative facilities, athletic centers, auditoriums, museums, and residential areas.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2011, *Travel + Leisure* recognized Cornell's campus in Ithaca as one of the most beautiful in the United States, praising its unique blend of architectural styles, historic landmarks, and picturesque surroundings.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Ithaca campus is characterized by an irregular layout and a mix of architectural styles that developed over time through successive master plans.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] More ornate buildings generally predate World War II, while later construction reflects modernist and contemporary styles.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Several Cornell University buildings have been listed on the National Register of Historic Places: Andrew Dickson White House, Bailey Hall, Caldwell Hall, the Computing and Communications Center, Morrill Hall, Rice Hall, Fernow Hall, Wing Hall, Llenroc, and Deke House.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Morrill Hall has also been designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Three other listed historic buildings, the original Roberts Hall, East Roberts Hall, and Stone Hall, were demolished in the 1980s to make way for new campus buildings and development.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The majority of Cornell University's academic and administrative facilities are located on its main campus in Ithaca.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Architectural styles range from ornate Collegiate Gothic, Victorian, and Neoclassical buildings to more spare international and modernist structures.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Frederick Law Olmsted, designer of Central Park, proposed a "grand terrace" overlooking Cayuga Lake in one of the earliest plans for the development of the campus.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] North Campus is primarily residential, with ten residence halls for first- and second-year students and housing for transfer students in the Townhouse Community.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The West Campus House System showcases a blend of architectural styles, including Gothic-style buildings and residence halls collectively known as "the Gothics".
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In Collegetown, located near the campus in Ithaca, the architectural styles are diverse, reflecting the area's mixed-use nature.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Schwartz Center for the Performing Arts and two upper-level residence halls are surrounded by a variety of apartment buildings, eateries, and businesses.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University's main campus in Ithaca is located in the Finger Lakes region in upstate New York and features views of the city, Cayuga Lake, and surrounding valleys.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The campus is bordered by two gorges, Fall Creek Gorge and Cascadilla Gorge.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The gorges are popular swimming spots during warmer months, but their use is discouraged by the university and city code due to potential safety hazards.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Adjacent to the main campus, Cornell owns the 2,800 acres (1,100 ha) Cornell Botanic Gardens, which feature cultivated gardens, arboretum collections, and natural areas.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University has implemented several green initiatives designed to promote sustainability and reduce environmental impact, including a gas-fired combined heat and power facility, an on-campus hydroelectric plant, and a lake source cooling system.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2007, Cornell established a Center for a Sustainable Future.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The same year, following a multiyear, cross-campus discussion about energy and sustainability, Cornell's Atkinson Center for Sustainability was established, funded by an $80 million gift from alumnus David R.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Atkinson ('60) and his wife Patricia, the largest gift ever received by Cornell from an individual at the time.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] A subsequent $30 million commitment in 2021 will name a new building on campus.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of 2020, the university, which committed to achieving net carbon neutrality by 2035, operates six solar farms that provide 28 megawatts of power.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell is developing an enhanced geothermal system, known as Earth Source Heating, designed to meet campus heating needs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2023, Cornell was the first university in the nation to commit to Kyoto Protocol emission reductions.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The same year, a concert held at Barton Hall by Dead & Company raised $3.1 million for MusiCares and the Cornell 2030 Project, which contributed to establishing the Climate Solutions Fund to catalyze large-scale climate research across the university, administered by the Atkinson Center.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's medical campus in New York City, also called Weill Cornell, is on the Upper East Side of Manhattan.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] It is home to two Cornell divisions, Weill Cornell Medicine, the university's medical school, and Weill Cornell Graduate School of Medical Sciences.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Since 1927, Weill Cornell has been affiliated with NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital, one of the nation's largest hospitals.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] While Cornell's medical school maintains its own faculty and academic divisions, it shares administrative and teaching hospital functions with Columbia University Medical Center.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In addition to NewYork-Presbyterian, Cornell's teaching hospitals include the Payne Whitney Clinic in Manhattan and its Westchester Division in White Plains, New York.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Weill Cornell Medical College is affiliated with neighboring Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, Rockefeller University, and the Hospital for Special Surgery.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Many faculty members have joint appointments at these institutions.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Weill Cornell, Rockefeller, and Memorial Sloan–Kettering offer the Tri-Institutional MD–PhD Program, which is available to selected entering Cornell medical students.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] From 1942 to 1979, the Weill Cornell Medical campus also housed the Cornell School of Nursing.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] On December 19, 2011, Cornell and Technion – Israel Institute of Technology in Haifa won a competition for rights to claim free city land and $100 million in subsidies to build an engineering campus in New York City.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The competition, established by former New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg, was designed to increase entrepreneurship and job growth in New York City's technology sector.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The winning bid consisted of a 2.1 million square foot state-of-the-art tech campus to be built on Roosevelt Island, on the site of the former Coler Specialty Hospital.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The following year, in fall 2012, instruction began at a temporary location in space donated by Google, at 111 Eighth Avenue in Manhattan.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2014, construction began on the Cornell Tech campus, and the first phase was completed in September 2017.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Thom Mayne of Morphosis Architects was selected to design Cornell Tech's first building.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In addition to the tech campus and medical center, Cornell maintains local offices in New York City for some of its service programs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Cornell Urban Scholars Program encourages students to pursue public service careers, arranging assignments with organizations working with New York City's poorest children, families, and communities.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The College of Human Ecology and College of Agriculture and Life Sciences enable students to reach out to local communities by gardening and building with the Cornell Cooperative Extension.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Students in the School of Industrial and Labor Relations' Extension and Outreach Program make workplace expertise available to organizations, union members, policymakers, and working adults.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The College of Engineering's Operations Research Manhattan, located in the city's Financial District, brings together business optimization research and decision support services used in financial applications and public health logistics planning.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2015, the College of Architecture, Art, and Planning opened an 11,000 square foot, Gensler-designed facility at 26 Broadway in Manhattan's Financial District.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In September 2004, Cornell opened the Weill Cornell Medical College in Qatar in Education City, near Doha, which is the first U.S. medical school established outside of the United States.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The college, which is a joint initiative with the Qatar government, is part of Cornell's efforts to increase its international influence.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The college, a full four-year MD program, mirrors the medical school curriculum taught at Weill Cornell Medicine in New York City.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The college also offers a two-year undergraduate pre-medical program, which has a separate admissions process and was established as an undergraduate program in September 2002 as the first coeducational institute of higher education in Qatar.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The college is partially funded by the Qatar government through the Qatar Foundation, a Qatar state-led non-profit organization, which contributed $750 million for its construction.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The medical center is housed in a large two-story structure designed by Arata Isozaki, a Japanese architect.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2004, the Qatar Foundation announced the construction of a 350-bed specialty teaching hospital near the medical college in Education City, which was to be completed in a few years.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University owns and operates a variety of off-campus research facilities and offers study abroad and scholarship programs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's off-campus research facilities include Shoals Marine Laboratory, a seasonal marine field station on Appledore Island off the Maine–New Hampshire coast, which is operated in conjunction with the University of New Hampshire and focuses on undergraduate education and research.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Until 2011, Cornell operated Arecibo Observatory in Puerto Rico, which was the site of the world's largest single-dish radio telescope.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Cornell Lab of Ornithology in Ithaca conducts research on biological diversity in birds.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Additional research facilities include the Animal Science Teaching and Research Center, the Duck Research Laboratory, the Cornell Biological Field Station, the Freeville Organic Research Farm, the Homer C.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Thompson Vegetable Research Farm, and biodiversity laboratories in Punta Cana in the Dominican Republic and the Peruvian Amazon.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell offers various study abroad and scholarship programs that allow students to gain experience and earn credit toward their degrees.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The "Capital Semester" program offers students the opportunity to intern in the New York State Legislature in Albany, the state capital.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Cornell in Washington program enables students to spend a semester in Washington, D.C., participating in research or internships.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Cornell in Rome program allows students to study architecture, urban studies, and the arts in Rome, Italy.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university is also a member of the Laidlaw Scholars program, which provides funding to undergraduates to conduct internationally focused research and foster leadership skills.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As New York state's land-grant university, Cornell operates a cooperative extension service, which includes 56 offices across the state.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] These offices provide programs in agriculture and food systems, children, youth and families, community and economic vitality, environment and natural resources, and nutrition and health.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university operates New York's Animal Health Diagnostic Center, which conducts animal disease control and husbandry.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell also operates eCornell, which provides online professional development and certificate programs and participates in New York's land-grant, sea-grant, and space-grant programs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University was chartered by an act of the New York State Legislature (Chapter 585 of the Laws of 1865) which was later codified into Article 115 (sections 5701 through 5716) of the Education Law of the Consolidated Laws of New York.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University is governed by a 64-member board of trustees, which includes both privately and publicly appointed trustees appointed by the Governor of New York, alumni-elected trustees, faculty-elected trustees, student-elected trustees, and non-academic staff-elected trustees.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Governor, Temporary President of the Senate, Speaker of the Assembly, and president of the university serve in *ex officio* voting capacities.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The board is responsible for electing a President to serve as the university's chief executive and educational officer.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] From 2014 to 2022, Robert Harrison served as chairman of the board.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Board of Trustees holds four regular meetings annually, which are subject to the New York State Open Meetings Law.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university charter (specifically, paragraph 1.b of section 5703 of the Education Law) provides that one member of the board, the life trustee, is the eldest living lineal descendant of Ezra Cornell.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of 2024, the current and longest-serving life trustee is Ezra Cornell, class of 1971, the great-great-great-grandson of the original Ezra Cornell.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] He celebrated 50 years of service as a board member in 2019.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] His eldest daughter Katy Cornell, class of 2001, is expected to become the next life trustee.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] On July 1, 2024, Michael Kotlikoff, who served as Cornell's 16th provost, began a two-year term as interim president, succeeding Martha E.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Pollack, Cornell's fourteenth president, who announced her retirement in May 2024.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's colleges and schools offer a wide range of undergraduate, graduate, and professional programs, including seven undergraduate colleges and seven schools offering graduate and professional programs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] All academic departments at Cornell are affiliated with at least one college.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Several inter-school academic departments offer courses in more than one college.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Students pursuing graduate degrees in these schools are enrolled in Cornell University Graduate School.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The School of Continuing Education and Summer Sessions provides additional programs for college and high school students, professionals, and other adults.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's four statutory colleges include the College of Agriculture and Life Sciences, College of Human Ecology, School of Industrial and Labor Relations, and College of Veterinary Medicine.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In the 2010–2011 fiscal year, these four colleges received $131.9 million in State University of New York (SUNY) appropriations to support teaching, research, and service missions, making them accountable to SUNY trustees and state agencies.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] New York residents enrolled in these colleges qualify for discounted tuition; however, their academic activities are considered by New York state to be private and non-state entities.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] They also do not offer discounted tuition for New York residents.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of 2023, among Cornell's 15,182 undergraduate students, 4,602 (30.3%) are affiliated with the College of Arts and Sciences, which is the largest college by enrollment, followed by 3,203 (21.1%) in Engineering, and 3,101 (20.4%) in Agriculture and Life Sciences.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The smallest of the seven undergraduate colleges is Architecture, Art, and Planning, with 503 (3.3%) students.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Philanthropy has played a central role in Cornell University's growth, funding major academic programs, research initiatives, and campus development.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of 2024, the university's endowment stands at $10.7 billion, making it the 14th-largest among U.S. universities.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2018, Cornell raised $743 million in private donations, ranking third behind Harvard University and Stanford University.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Major single-donor contributions in recent decades have significantly shaped Cornell's professional schools.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 1998, Weill Cornell Medicine was renamed after a $100 million gift from Sanford I.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Weill, a 1955 alumnus and former Citibank CEO.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] By 2013, the Weills' total donations exceeded $600 million.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2017, Herbert Fisk Johnson III, an alumnus and chairman of S.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Johnson & Son, donated $150 million to support the Cornell Johnson Graduate School of Management, one of the largest gifts to a business school.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell Tech, the university's technology-focused graduate campus on Roosevelt Island, has received major philanthropic support.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2011, Chuck Feeney, a 1956 alumnus and founder of DFS Group, became Cornell's largest private donor, contributing $1 billion to fund the campus and other initiatives.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Jacobs, a 1956 alumnus and Qualcomm founder, and his wife, Joan, donated $133 million to establish the Jacobs Technion-Cornell Institute at Cornell Tech.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Other major gifts have supported research and sustainability efforts.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2010, David and Patricia Atkinson donated $80 million to establish the Atkinson Center for a Sustainable Future, funding research on environmental and sustainability challenges.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell is a large and primarily residential research university, and a majority of its students are enrolled in undergraduate programs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Since 1921, the university has been accredited by the Middle States Commission on Higher Education and its predecessor.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell operates on a 4–1–4 academic calendar, with the fall term beginning in late August and ending in early December, a three-week winter session in January, and the spring term beginning in late January and ending in early May.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell is a land-, space-, and sea-grant university, and until 2014 was a sun-grant university as well.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Admission to Cornell University is highly competitive.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's undergraduate programs for the Class of 2028 received 65,612 applications, of which 5,516 (8.4%) were accepted.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] For enrolling first-year students, the middle-50% range for SAT evidence-based reading and writing was 730–770, while for mathematics it was 770–800; the middle-50% range for the ACT composite was 33–35.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university attracts a diverse student body.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2022, the proportion of admitted students who self-identify as underrepresented minorities increased to 34.2%, up from 33.7% in 2021, and 59.3% self-identify as students of color, up from 52.5% in 2017 and 57.2% in 2020.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Among the 5,168 admitted in 2022, 1,163 were first-generation college students, up from 844 in 2020.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university practices need-blind admission for U.S. applicants.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University, under Section 9 of its original charter, ensures equal access to education by admitting students without distinction based on rank, class, occupation, or locality.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The charter also mandates free instruction for one student from each Assembly district in New York State.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] From the 1950s to the 1980s, Cornell collaborated with other Ivy League institutions to establish a uniform financial aid system.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Although a 1989 consent decree ended this collaboration due to an antitrust investigation, all Ivy League schools still offer need-based financial aid without athletic scholarships.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In December 2010, Cornell pledged to match the grant component of financial aid offers from the seven other Ivy League schools and MIT and Stanford for accepted applicants considering these institutions.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2008, Cornell introduced a financial aid initiative that incrementally replaced need-based loans with scholarships for undergraduate students from lower-income families.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Despite a 27% drop in the university's endowment in 2008, attributable partly to the 2008 financial crisis, Cornell president David J.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Skorton allocated additional funds to continue the initiative and sought to raise $125 million in donations for its support.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2010, Cornell met the full financial aid needs of 40% of full-time first-year students with financial need.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The average undergraduate student debt upon graduation, as of 2010, was $21,549.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell offers a wide range of undergraduate majors with an international focus, including African Studies, Asian-Pacific American Studies, French Studies, German Studies, Jewish Studies, Latino Studies, Near Eastern Studies, Romance Studies, and Russian Literature.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Students have the opportunity to study abroad on six continents through various programs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Asian Studies major, the Southeast Asia Program, and the China and Asia-Pacific Studies (CAPS) major provide opportunities for students and researchers focusing on Asia.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell has an agreement with Peking University that allows CAPS students to spend a semester in Beijing.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In the Middle East, Cornell's efforts are centered on biology and medicine.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Weill Cornell Medical College in Qatar trains new doctors to improve health services in the region.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university is also involved in developing the Bridging the Rift Center, a “Library of Life,” a database of all living systems, on the Israel–Jordan border, in collaboration with those two countries and Stanford University.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell offers several joint degree programs with international universities.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell has partnered with Queen's University in Ontario to offer a joint Executive MBA program, which affords its graduates MBA degrees from both universities.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell also offers an international consulting course in association with the Indian Institute of Management Bangalore.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University has been routinely ranked among the top academic institutions in the nation and world by independent ranking assessments.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2024, Cornell was ranked 10th in the U.S. and 12th in the world by *QS World University Rankings* and 20th in the world by *Times Higher Education World University Rankings*.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2023, the university was ranked 10th in the U.S. by *The Washington Monthly,* which factors research, community service, social mobility, and sustainability into its ratings.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In its annual edition of “America's Best Architecture & Design Schools,” the journal *Design Intelligence* ranked Cornell's Bachelor of Architecture program best in the nation for much of the 21st century, including from 2000 to 2002, 2005 to 2007, 2009 to 2013, and 2015 to 2016.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In its 2011 survey, the program ranked first and the Master of Architecture program ranked sixth nationally.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2017, *Design Intelligence* ranked Cornell's Master of Landscape Architecture program fourth in the nation and its Bachelor of Science in Landscape Architecture program fifth nationally.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Among business schools in the U.S., *Forbes* ranked the Cornell Johnson Graduate School of Management ninth nationally in 2019.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2020, *The Washington Post* ranked the school eighth for salary potential, and *Poets & Quants* ranked it 13th nationally, fourth in the nation for investment banking, and sixth globally for salary.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Cornell Johnson Graduate School of Management was ranked 11th nationally by *Bloomberg Businessweek* in 2019, and 11th nationally and 14th globally by *The Economist*.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2013, the Johnson school was ranked second for sustainability by *Bloomberg Businessweek*.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's international relations program is ranked among the best in the world by *Foreign Policy* magazine's Inside the Ivory Tower survey, which ranked Cornell's undergraduate program 12th and its doctorate program 11th in 2012.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2015, Cornell was ranked third among New York colleges and universities for professor salaries.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of 2020, Cornell University Library, with more than 10 million holdings, is the 13th-largest academic library in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] It was the first among U.S. colleges and universities to allow undergraduates to borrow books from its libraries.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2006, The Princeton Review ranked it the 11th-best college library, and in 2009, it climbed to sixth.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University Press, established in 1869 but inactive from 1884 to 1930, was the first university publishing enterprise in the United States.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's academic units and student groups publish multiple scholarly journals, including at least five faculty-led and seven student-led publications.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University is classified among “R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity.” The National Science Foundation ranked Cornell 14th among U.S. universities for R&D expenditures in 2021, at $1.18 billion.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Department of Health and Human Services and the National Science Foundation are the primary federal sponsors, accounting for 49.6% and 24.4% of federal support, respectively.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell is ranked fourth worldwide for producing graduates who pursue PhDs in engineering or natural sciences at American institutions and fifth for graduates pursuing PhDs in any field.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell has contributed to nuclear and high-energy physics, space exploration, automotive safety, and computing technology.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] It regularly ranks among top U.S. universities for patenting and startup formation.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2004–05, Cornell filed 203 U.S. patent applications, completed 77 license agreements, and distributed more than $4.1 million in royalties to units and inventors; in 2009 it spent $671 million on science and engineering R&D, 16th nationally.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell has participated in uncrewed Mars missions since 1962 and played a leading role in the Mars Exploration Rover mission.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Its researchers helped discover the rings of Uranus and operated the Arecibo Observatory in Puerto Rico until 2011, then home to the world's largest single-dish radio telescope.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Founded in 1952, the Automotive Crash Injury Research Center pioneered modern crash test research, including early cadaver studies that informed seat belts, energy-absorbing steering wheels, padded dashboards, and improved door locks.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell has also advanced parallel computing and research cyberinfrastructure.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In high-energy physics, Cornell built the second U.S. cyclotron in the 1930s, became the first to study synchrotron radiation in the 1950s, and operates the Cornell Electron Storage Ring beneath Alumni Field, once the world's highest-luminosity electron–positron collider.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Faculty including Hans Bethe contributed to the Manhattan Project.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell groups participate in the design of the proposed International Linear Collider, envisioned to complement the Large Hadron Collider and probe questions related to dark matter and extra dimensions.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Sage School of Philosophy was founded in 1891 with support from Henry W.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Sage in memory of Susan Linn Sage; that year it also launched *The Philosophical Review*, one of the first sustained U.S. journals devoted to philosophy.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Notable scholars have included Max Black, Edwin A.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Burtt, Norman Malcolm, John Rawls, George Holland Sabine, and Gregory Vlastos.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In a 2024 reputation ranking by the *Philosophical Gourmet*, the Sage School ranked 16th in the U.S.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of 2024, faculty include Tad Brennan, John Doris, Rachana Kamtekar, Kate Manne, Julia Markovits, Andrei Marmor, Shaun Nichols, and Derk Pereboom.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of 2016–2017, Cornell had over 1,000 registered student organizations, spanning club and varsity sports, performing arts (including multiple a cappella groups), political and cultural groups, media, games, and outdoor clubs.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Cornell International Affairs Society fields a traveling Model UN team and hosts a large high school conference; the Cornell University Mock Trial Association regularly qualifies for national competition.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell United Religious Work coordinates programming across faith traditions; the Cornell Catholic Community is the largest single religious student organization.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Music groups include a symphony orchestra, concert bands, and choral ensembles, including the Glee Club and the Chordials.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Big Red Marching Band performs at athletic and campus events.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Founded in 1868, the Cornell University Glee Club is Cornell's oldest student organization.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell Outdoor Education and Outdoor Odyssey run outdoor courses and pre-orientation trips; the Cornell Astronomical Society hosts public observing nights at Fuertes Observatory.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university is home to Telluride House and three long-standing honor societies: Sphinx Head, Der Hexenkreis, and Quill and Dagger.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's student governments—the Student Assembly and the Graduate and Professional Student Assembly—collectively allocate about $3.0 million annually to support clubs and organizations.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell hosts a large fraternity and sorority system with about 70 chapters; roughly 33% of men and 24% of women participate.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Zeta Psi was chartered during Cornell's first year.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Alpha Phi Alpha, the first intercollegiate fraternity established for African Americans, was founded at Cornell in 1906.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Alpha Zeta (1890) was the first Greek-letter organization founded in the U.S. for Latin Americans.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] La Unidad Latina, Lambda Upsilon Lambda (1982), later became the only Latino-based fraternity with chapters at all Ivy League institutions; Lambda Pi Chi (1988) was the first Latina-based (not Latina-exclusive) sorority founded at an Ivy League university.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Many Cornell chapters are among the oldest in their national organizations.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Alpha Delta Phi chapter house (1877) is believed to be the first U.S. building constructed solely for fraternity use; the chapter's current home was designed by John Russell Pope.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Greek system reports substantial annual community service and philanthropy; serious conduct matters are handled by the university's judicial processes.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Student-run newspapers include *The Cornell Daily Sun*, an independent daily, and *The Cornell Review*, a conservative biweekly.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Other outlets include *The Cornell Lunatic* (humor), the *Cornell Chronicle* (university paper of record), and *Kitsch Magazine*, co-published with Ithaca College.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] *The Cornellian*, an independent organization, publishes the yearbook, which has received the Silver Crown Award for Journalism and the Benjamin Franklin Award for Print Design.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Students also operate WVBR-FM, an independent commercial FM station, and various internet streams.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's residential system comprises North Campus, West Campus, and Collegetown.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Coeducational housing began in 1971, and the university maintains a system of residential advisors.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] A 1997 initiative designated West Campus primarily for upper-level students and North Campus for first-years and some sophomores.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2022, the North Campus Residential Expansion added beds for about 800 sophomores.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] West Campus incorporates a residential college system developed through a $250 million project, influenced in part by Risley Residential College.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Other options include Schuyler House (a former part of Sage Infirmary).
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As of 2025, The Princeton Review ranked Cornell's dining program fifth in the nation.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The university operates 29 dining facilities across campus.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] On North Campus, Morrison Dining and North Star Dining at Appel Commons serve as primary venues for first-year students.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Risley Residential College includes a historic dining hall modeled on the great hall at Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell's 35 varsity intercollegiate teams compete in NCAA Division I as the Cornell Big Red, primarily in the Ivy League and the Eastern College Athletic Conference (ECAC).
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Teams frequently contend nationally in men's wrestling, men's lacrosse, men's ice hockey, and rowing.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] As an Ivy member, Cornell does not award athletic scholarships.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Football claimed at least a share of the national championship four times before 1940 and has won three Ivy titles, most recently in 1990.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2010, men's basketball reached the NCAA “Sweet 16,” the first Ivy team to do so since 1979.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell runs one of the largest collegiate outdoor education programs in the U.S., serving over 20,000 people annually with more than 130 courses (e.g., backpacking, caving, climbing, sailing).
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] COE also runs the student-led pre-orientation program Outdoor Odyssey.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Most COE classes are taught by paid student instructors and count toward the physical education requirement.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] The Lindseth Climbing Wall was renovated in 2016 to 8,000 sq ft of climbing surface (from 4,800 sq ft).
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornelliana refers to Cornell traditions, legends, and lore.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Traditions include Slope Day and Dragon Day, one of the oldest campus events (founded 1901 and usually held near St.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] First-year architecture students build and parade a dragon around central campus, followed by upper-class architecture students in costume; the historic bonfire has been discontinued due to environmental regulations.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Campus lore includes myths about statues on the Arts Quad and a “kissing bridge” on North Campus.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Notable pranks include a 60-pound pumpkin and a disco ball mysteriously placed atop the 173-foot McGraw Tower spire; the tower is lit seasonally and plays music.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] School colors are carnelian and white; the unofficial mascot is a bear, dating to the live bear “Touchdown” introduced in 1915.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell provides professional and peer counseling services, and on-campus outpatient care through Cornell Health (formerly Gannett Health Services), with emergency and residential services provided by Cayuga Medical Center.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Historically, Cornell maintained residential infirmary care, including at the former Sage Infirmary.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell offers reproductive health and family-planning services and operates a student-run Emergency Medical Service (CUEMS) that responds on campus and provides training.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] In 2009–10, six student deaths by gorge jumping drew national attention.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Temporary bridge fences were followed by installation of means-restriction nets on five bridges in 2013.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Prior to that cluster, Cornell's suicide rate had been similar to or below that of peer U.S. universities, including 2005–2008 when no suicides occurred.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] Cornell University Police are New York State peace officers with authority equivalent to municipal police in Ithaca.
[src:cornell-university/cornell-university] They provide 24/7 patrols, emergency response, crime prevention, investigations, and enforcement of state laws and campus regulations.
